<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GirlKilled     10-15 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Girl Killed,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Girl Dead, Four Adults Arrested</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PD1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OREGON CITY, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was charged Friday in the beating
death of the 8-year-old daughter of the leader of a Los
Angeles-based religious group once known as Ecclesia.
   Dayna Lorea Broussard had been beaten and whipped, said state
Medical Examiner Larry Lewman. The girl apparently lived at one of
two homes outside Portland occupied by children and others
affiliated with the group.
   Police charged Willie K. Chambers, of Los Angeles, with murder
and three others with hindering prosecution.
   The four adults brought the child to a Clackamas County fire
station in the rural Happy Valley area about 20 miles east of
Portland. The child was dead on arrival at the fire station,
authorities said.
   County sheriff's deputies removed 55 children from a house in
Happy Valley Friday and a state agency was seeking custody, said
Alice Galloway, spokeswoman for the Oregon Children's Services
Division.
   Carolyn Van Brunt, dean of the Watts Christian Center school and
training program in Los Angeles, said the dead girl was the
daughter of Eldridge Broussard Jr., who founded the Ecclesia
Athletic Association in the Watts area of Los Angeles as a combined
religious-recreational institution in 1975.
   She said the girl was one of about 50 children from the center
who had spent the summer months in Oregaon. She said the child's
father had been in Los Angeles developing a youth center.
   Broussard, who played basketball as a freshman at the University
of Oregon and later starred as a basketball player for Pacific
University in Forest Grove, Ore., once defined Ecclesia's Christian
mission as recreation of people's attitudes and goals through
recreation.
   The group developed a 32-team basketball league and opened a
school, sporting goods store and silkscreening service, among other
operations.
</TEXT>
