<1ST_LINE>u a AM-UNDues     10-15 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN Dues,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Withholds Portion Of UN Dues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States will continue to withhold part
of its United Nations dues this year until a key U.N. committee
approves a new austerity budget and other administrative changes
occur, administration officials say.
   United Nations officials say the action is contributing to a new
cash crisis the organization might face later this year, The New
York Times reported in its Saturday editions.
   President Reagan last month ordered the immediate payment of $44
million in outstanding U.S. dues owed for fiscal 1988, which ended
Sept. 30. He said he was satisfied the organization was making good
progress in carrying out administrative changes.
   On Friday, the Reagan administration gave the United Nations a
check for $85.6 million, which is a portion of the $144 million
Congress appropriated for the organization for the 1989 fiscal
year, the Times said.
   The remaining $59 million will be withheld until the
administration sees the result of the committee's work and
documentation to prove the United Nations is carrying out budgetary
and administrative changes, the paper said.
   The Fifth Committee of the General Assembly, which oversees the
U.N.'s finances, is still considering a new austerity budget
adopted by a smaller committee last month, it said.
   The Times said the withholding of the money has angered senior
United Nations officials. It said some of them suspect that
right-wing American officials are trying to keep the United Nations
short of money to make it more vulnerable to pressure.
   The United States still owes the United Nations and its
specialized agencies, such as the World Health Organization, $520
million in past debts. The White House ordered the State Department
to work out a multiyear plan for repaying the debt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
