<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Haiti     10-15 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Haiti,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protesters Demand That Priest Stay In Haiti</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Thousands of chanting youths
marched for a second day near a burned-out church to protest
reports that Roman Catholic officials ordered a radical priest out
of Haiti.
   Soldiers fired in the air to disperse some of the demonstrators
who burned tires across the road leading to the city's airport. The
youths set the fires after rumors spread that Rev. Jean Bertrand
Aristide was about to leave the country, radio stations said.
   Bishop Guire Poulard, bishop of the southern town of Jacmel,
said on the Roman Catholic Church's Radio Soleil that the rumor of
Aristide's imminent departure was unfounded.
   About 6,000 demonstrators marched for three hours Friday from
the ruins of St. Jean Bosco Church, where Aristide was pastor, to
the headquarters of the Haitian Bishops Conference in Pacot. The
same 2{-mile route was traced by about 6,000 protesters Thursday.
   The bishops conference on Sunday condemned the radical wing of
the church headed by Aristide for allegedly preaching ``violence
and class warfare.''
   The youths, enthusiastic but orderly, chanted slogans calling on
the church to change its mind and allow Aristide to remain.
   Aristide, one of the most popular figures in Haiti, was an
outspoken critic of Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy's regime. Namphy was
ousted by rank-and-file soldiers in a coup Sept. 17 and replaced by
Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril.
   On Sept. 11, Aristide was saying Mass at his St. Jean Bosco
Church when thugs attacked parishioners, killing at least 12,
wounding 70 and burning down the church. The soldiers that led the
coup cited that massacre and other state-sponsored violence as
reasons for seizing power.
   On Monday, Aristide said in a statement read on Radio Soleil
that he had received a message from Rome ordering him to leave
Haiti by Oct. 17.
   Aristide did not specify who issued the order, but Stephane
Francisque, a close friend, said the priest's Salesian Order had
told him to report to the Saint Claire parish of Montreal, Canada.
   Two previous church orders transferring Aristide to remote
parishes in Haiti were withdrawn after popular protests.
   Aristide, an advocate of liberation theology which encourages
the poor to demand social justice, has been criticized by the
Haitian Bishops Conference for allegedly preaching ``violence and
class struggle.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
