<DOCNO> AP881015-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-88 0129EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Nigeria     10-15 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Nigeria,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Touts Nigerian Economic Revival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The promise of Nigeria's military leaders to
restore civilian rule in 1990 is unconditional and not linked to
economic progress, says one of the African country's top government
officials.
   The transition to democracy ``is not conditioned on Nigeria's
being able to achieve economic growth ... in 1990 there will
definitely be assembly elections,'' Chief Samuel Oluyemi Falae told
reporters Friday.
   Falae, a veteran fiscal and planning official who has served
since 1986 as secretary to the military government that came to
power three years ago in a coup led by Maj. Gen. Ibrahim Babangida
met with U.S. government and congressional leaders and officials of
the World Bank and International Monetary Fund here during the past
week.
   during his visit he also flew to Houston, Texas, where a number
of expatriate Nigerians and Nigerian-Americans live and planned
other talks next week in New York before returning home.
   Falae said the message he brought from Nigeria is that Africa's
most populous country is on the way to recovery from near economic
collapse in the mid-1980s, and that it welcomes foreign investment.
   ``I am not saying Nigeria has become a paradise on earth'' for
business, but that ``individual businessmen now have a better
chance to operate,'' he said.
   The pre-1985 Nigerian government discouraged investment by
imposing long delays and requiring multiple approvals, Falae said.
A single agency of government now deals with foreign investment
proposals and is required to reply in a maximum of 30 days, he
said, adding that declaration and repatriation of dividends have
been simplified.
   Nigeria has undertaken currency devaluation, liberalization of
licensing requirements, consumer austerity and other reforms
prescribed by the World Bank and IMF, in some cases tougher than
those demanded, ``leaving us with flexibility,'' he said.
   Fourteen months after the 1985 coup, the World Bank also
signaled revived confidence in Nigeria with a loan of $452 million,
the largest ever for an African country. The bank praised the
Babangida government for ``courageous and very difficult''
austerity measures that it said justified support from the
financial community.
   After five years of decline in output, the economy is showing
signs of growth, Falae said. ``We have been sailing through a
narrow gorge, and beyond us is a wide open bay.''
   Nigeria, with a population of more than 100 million, has sharply
reduced its dependence on crude oil exports with increased sales of
non-oil manufactured products and also hopes to begin exporting
natural gas, Falae said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
