<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     10-15 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>How Does Bush Rate His Debate Performance? ``Read My Smile''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top prospects uncertain</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   How does Vice President George Bush rate his
debate performance against rival Michael Dukakis? ``Read my
smile,'' he suggests.
   However, the Republican presidential nominee also said he wasn't
taking anything for granted, despite recent polls showing his lead
over the Massachusetts governor to be widening.
   ``When the polls were going the other way, I said `it isn't
over.' And it wasn't. So why should I now suddenly have the luxury
of changing my position?
   ``Watch how hard we work,'' Bush told reporters traveling with
him on Air Force Two on his way back here from a campaign event in
San Diego.
   Bush today wraps up a five-day California visit with a bus tour
of state's Central Valley, with rallies planned in Stockton,
Modesto, Merced and Fresno.
   He was to spend the rest of the weekend in Denver.
   Bush aides view California as critical, and suggest that it
could go either way.
   Speaking at the Scripps Institution of Oceanography on Friday in
San Diego, Bush said if elected one of his first acts in office
would be to seek passage of stronger clean-air legislation.
   He also called for ``a very close look'' at whether proposed new
oil drilling of the coast of Southern California might harm the
environment before going ahead with federal approval for the
drilling.
   ``I oppose drilling in those environmentally sensitive areas
where the risk of damage is too great,'' he said.
   Earlier, Bush said he would oppose new drilling in Northern
California ``pending resolution of these environmental concerns.''
   Bush's suggestion that reporters ``read my smile'' was a takeoff
on his frequently used campaign speech line: ``Read my lips: no new
taxes.''
   The vice president said he did not think he would become
overconfident as a result in what was widely viewed as a good
showing in the final debate.
   Of the questions asked, Bush said: ``I thought the questions ...
were as good as any I've ever had in any of the debates ... I can't
say I welcomed them. But they were good questions.''
   Bush and his wife, Barbara, dined Friday night with Los Angeles
Dodgers manager Tommy Lasorda. Bush called him ``an old friend.''
   Asked why he wasn't with his team plotting strategy for the
upcoming first World Series game, Lasorda cracked: ``I'm getting
all my advice from right here,'' indicating Bush.
</TEXT>
