<HEAD>Quotes From the Presidential Campaign Trail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some comments Friday from the
presidential campaign trail:
   
   MICHAEL DUKAKIS, assailing his Republican rival with renewed
vigor: ``Think of where we'll be four years from now if we try to
get by on Mr. Bush's diet of old chestnuts, new baloney and the
same old voodoo stew.''
   
   GEORGE BUSH, assessing his performance in Thursday's debate:
``We were specific on the issues. We came at each other pretty
hard. And when the smoke cleared it was pretty clear where we stood
and I believe that I moved my campaign forward by what happened
last night.''
   
   LLOYD BENTSEN, with some choice words on Bush's debate-night
performance: ``Debating George Bush is just like trying to eat
Jell-O with a fork. It keeps slipping off, sliding off, and when
you finally get a bite there's not much substance to it, just a lot
of sugar water and artificial ingredients.''
   
   DAN QUAYLE, stepping up his criticism of the Massachusetts
governor: ``The political liability happens to be Governor
Dukakis.''
   
   LEE ATWATER, Bush campaign manager, tempering confidence with
cautiousness in the waning days of the campaign: ``This election is
going to be won or lost in the last three weeks. We're not going to
take anything for granted. ... If the campaign gets smug or
overconfident, we're going to be in trouble in a matter of days.
These big states are all still very close.''
</TEXT>
