<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mexico-NukePlant     10-15 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Nuke Plant,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Go-Ahead Given For Mexico's First Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has authorized loading of fuel
and eventual start-up of the nation's first nuclear power plant,
but environmental groups threaten to fight it with civil
disobedience.
   The approval came after government specialists testified for a
week before both houses of Congress and opponents pledged to block
roads and hold a mass sit-in.
   Assistant Energy Secretary Jose Luis Alcudia announced the
government's decision Friday to allow the Laguna Verda plant to
move forward.
   The first of two 657-megawatt reactors will be fully operational
after six months of loading fuel and operating tests, officials
said. The second reactor is to be ready by 1991.
   A joint communique of the Energy and Ecology departments Friday
night said the government ``is assuming this responsibility with
the absolute conviction that Laguna Verde is convenient for the
country and will not pose problems for the health and well-being of
the population.''
   The statement said the government had devised adequate security
and evacuation plans for the plant in case of accident. It said
these had been sanctioned by the U.S. Institute of Nuclear Power
Operations and the International Atomic Energy Organization.
   It said the electricity generated by Laguna Verde each year
would save 14 million barrels of combustible fuels.
   The plant, 200 miles east of Mexico City in Veracruz state, was
ready for the loading of radioactive fuel in December. But
President Miguel de la Madrid postponed plans after protests by
environmental groups.
   Mexico's leading ecology and anti-nuclear organizations vowed to
mount a protest rally on Sunday in Palma Sola, three miles from the
plant.
   Jose Arias Chavez, leader of the Pact of Ecological Groups, said
demonstrators would block roads and possibly attempt to occupy the
grounds of the nuclear plant. Similar demonstrations were planned
throughout the country, he said.
   He said protesters wanted to avoid ``the nuclearization of
Mexico.''
</TEXT>
