<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Cyprus-Vassiliou     10-15 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cyprus-Vassiliou,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cyprus President Optimistic About Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President George Vassiliou says he is
optimistic about resuming talks next week on reuniting his country
after years of being split into Greek Cypriot and Turkish Cypriot
sectors.
   ``I wish that the peace epidemic affecting the whole world might
reach Cyprus. ... I'm hopeful an agreement can be reached,''
Vassiliou told a four-member panel of Cypriot journalists in a
television interview Friday.
   Vassiliou appeared on state-run television a day after returning
to the Mediterranean island from a 10-day trip to the United
States, Britain and France.
   ``My message was that the international climate of detente
should assist in the search for a Cyprus settlement and that the
time for this is more propitious than ever,'' he said, but added he
doesn't ``expect a settlement overnight.''
   Vassiliou and his Turkish Cypriot counterpart, Rauf Denktash,
resume their reunification talks next week. They have met four
times since U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar kicked
off the negotiations on Aug. 25 in Geneva.
   The U.N. chief has set a June 1989 deadline for the talks.
Vassiliou and Denktash will go to New York next month to review
progress.
   The two leaders have agreed on a bi-zonal federation for Cyprus
but differences remain over the withdrawal of about 35,000 Turkish
troops and 50,000 Turkish settlers from the northern third of the
island.
   Cyprus was partitioned in 1974 when Turkey invaded after an
Athens-inspired coup against the late President Makarios.
</TEXT>
