<DOCNO> AP881015-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-88 0224EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Algeria     10-15 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Algeria,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moslem Fundamentalists Demand Freedoms in Algeria</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Islamic fundamentalists reacting to a
week of widespread riots have called for an end to emergency
regulations, a national minimum wage, civic freedoms, and more
vigorous promotion of Islam.
   Their 12-point program called for an end to a state of
emergency. The government imposed a six-day state of emergency
during the rioting, but the fundamentalists said such rules had
actually been in force since 1962, when Algeria became independent
from France.
   ``The time has come to let the people speak,'' said Ali Belhadj,
an imam at the Al Sunna mosque in the Bab-el-Oued quarter, a
fundamentalist stronghold. The religious leader read the program
before worshipers at Friday prayers.
   Riots broke out Oct. 4 in Algiers and provincial cities over
shortages, high food prices and the government's program of
austerity and economic reform. Several days of fragile calm have
followed a week of unrest.
   Belhadj was among fundamentalist leaders who organized rallies
trying to focus discontent on religious as well as economic issues.
   The fundamentalists' program stopped short of demanding an
Islamic state in Algeria, which already declares Islam the official
religion but operates in secular style with emphasis on strict
socialist policies.
   It called for an end to nepotism and feudalism in the
administration, amnesty for all political prisoners, an unspecified
guaranteed minimum wage, the unrestricted freedom to spread Islam,
and fundamental freedoms to allow people ``to manage their own
affairs.''
   The program also called for freedom of association and
expression, freedom to criticize the state, judicial reform,
amendment of legislation to eliminate ``any notion contrary to
Islam,'' reform of education to promote Islam, and freedom of the
press.
   The government has said 180 people died in the rioting, but
Algerian officials said on condition of anonymity that many more
were killed.
   Unofficial reports said 500 or more died. More than 1,000 people
were injured, according to reliable accounts from hospitals and
other sources.
   The official Algerian news agency on Friday accused French news
media of trying to provoke conflicts among Algerians, but it did
not cite examples. The Algerie Presse Service said the French press
was plotting against ``the sacred principle of Algeria's unity.''
   Most French newspapers have carried commentaries suggesting that
their government and French intellectuals have been too slow to
condemn the killings of unarmed protesters by Algerian troops.
   An Associated Press photographer, Roberto Pfeil, was detained
Friday while taking pictures of Moslem worshipers and expelled from
Algeria. The government gave no explanation.
   On Wednesday, President Chadli Bendjedid announced a ``process
of democratization,'' beginning with a national referendum Nov. 3
on making the prime minister responsible to the National Assembly.
   Details of Bendjedid's broad proposals have not become clear,
but they appear to point toward loosening the state structure built
by his predecessor, Houari Boumedienne.
   Boumedienne, who kept tight control for 13 years, died 10 years
ago, and Bendjedid was elected to replace him. Almost immediately,
he sought to weaken the system in which the ruling National
Liberation Front party kept tight rein on the nation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
