<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-USPayment     10-15 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-US Payment,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Hands Over $85.6 Million But Still Owes Millions More</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has given a check for
$85.6 million to the United Nations, but Washington owes millions
more that the Reagan administration withheld pending U.N. austerity
measures.
   U.S. Ambassador Vernon A. Walters delivered the money during a
surprise visit Friday to Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar.
The check reduced the U.S. debt to the regular budget to $366.3
million.
   A U.N. statement said the payment was the second installment of
the $188 million President Reagan promised to pay by the end of the
year. The United States earlier paid $15.2 million.
   The payment was made one day after the Soviet Union, which is
paying its own arrears, pledged the equivalent of $600 million to
U.N. relief and reconstruction efforts in Afghanistan.
   ``The United Nations remains financially weakened and unstable
because reserves are substantially depleted,'' said a U.N.
statement.
   ``If this situation is not corrected, it could impede the
carrying out of new peace missions,'' it said, referring to U.N
peacekeeping forces currently in the Persian Gulf and new forces
planned for southern Africa and eventually for Cambodia.
   Since Reagan took office eight years ago his administration has
harshly criticized the United Nations for what it calls
anti-Western bias, bureaucracy and waste.
   The administration withheld part of U.S. regular budget dues to
the U.N., some peacekeeping dues and other fees in order to
pressure the world body into fiscal and administrative reforms.
   Reagan recently acknowledged that the U.N. had made progress in
reforms and pledged to pay back the withheld dues by the end of
this year and the rest over several years.
   But U.S. officials said Washington will continue to withhold $59
million in dues promised this year until a key U.N. committee
approves a new austerity budget and other administrative changes,
The New York Times reported in today's editions.
   The Fifth Committee of the General Assembly, which oversees the
U.N.'s finances, is still considering a new austerity budget
adopted by a smaller committee last month, it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
