<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CounterfeitChecks     10-15 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Counterfeit Checks,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agents Seize $39 Million In Counterfeit Traveler's Checks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities arrested 10 alleged counterfeiters and
seized more than $39 million in phony traveler's checks after some
of the fake checks were used for cash, cocaine and shopping sprees.
   The suspects, from Israel, Finland, Colombia and Florida, were
rounded up Friday after a federal grand jury returned an indictment
charging them with conspiracy and counterfeiting.
   ``This is the largest seizure of a counterfeit traveler's check
operation in U.S. history,'' Jack Kippenberger, a U.S. Secret
Service agent, said at a news conference where he was surrounded by
stacks of seized checks and printing plates used to make them.
   The alleged ringleader was Simon Gabay, 38, an Israeli national
who ran a cosmetics distribution company and owned a print shop in
North Miami, Kippenberger said.
   ``He was the brains behind the whole operation,'' the agent
said. ``He had the plates and had the print shop where all the
money-making went on.''
   If convicted, Gabay could face up to 75 years in prison and a $5
million fine.
   Undercover Secret Service agents, who stumbled upon the
check-printing scheme as part of an investigation of currency
counterfeiting, made several purchases of checks over a four-month
period, Kippenberger said.
   While most of the checks were seized, an undetermined amount
were traded for cash and cocaine and about $40,000 in checks were
used to buy merchandise at stores along the East Coast, agents said.
   ``It imposes a severe loss, a sometimes catastrophic loss, on
those who receive them,'' said U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen.
``It's those in the innocent public who suffer the loss.''
</TEXT>
