<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Burma     10-15 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four More Killed, Burma's Elections to Be Held No Sooner Than 1989</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers killed four more people in the
military government's crackdown on unrest, state-run radio
reported, and officials said elections will not be held before next
year.
   The latest killings, reported Friday, lifted to more than 450
the official count of people slain by troops since a Sept. 18
military coup.
   The radio said two of the dead were looters, and the others were
shot when they ran away after troops stopped them for violating
curfew.
   The killings follow pro-democracy protests that began after Ne
Win, who seized power in a military coup 26 years ago, stepped down
in July. Two more governments fell during widespread protests, but
hardline Gen. Saw Maung seized power Sept. 18 and ordered troops to
shoot if necessary.
   He also promised general elections within about three months.
   ``All arrangements are expected to be ready by early next year,
and the date for holding of elections will be decided after
consultation with political parties,'' the chairman of the
government's election commission, Ba Htay, told representatives of
registered parties on Friday in a statement carried by Rangoon
radio.
   Eighteen parties have officially registered, but none has said
if it will participate in elections run by the government.
   The National Unity Party, which under a different name was
Burma's sole political for 26 years, is expected to have the
support of the government and military.
   The chairman said registered parties may open branches
throughout the country after consultation with ``law and order
restoration councils,'' which were set up by Saw Maung. The parties
will be allowed to carry out organizational work on their own
premises, although a ban on public meetings of more than five
people is still in force.
   The commission head said, ``The commission will try its best to
hold a free and fair general election.''
</TEXT>
