<DOCNO> AP881015-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-88 0412EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Koreas     10-15 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koreas,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Korea Welcomes South's Summit Proposal, But Not Roh</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea welcomed a proposal by South Korean
President Roh Tae-woo for summit talks on reunification of the two
Koreas, but said Roh himself is not welcome in the North, an
official news report said today.
   The North's Korean Central News Agency quoted a statement Friday
by the government's Committee for the Peaceful Reunification of the
Fatherland as saying the proposal by Roh for talks ``deserves
welcome.''
   But it said that despite Roh's willingness to visit Pyongyang,
the North Korean capital, ``he has no justification to come to the
North.''
   ``Under the stringent anti-communist system of South Korea, the
South Korean leading authority himself, who is willing to come to
Pyongyang to discuss the reunification proposal, would be charged
by law and would never get off scott-free,'' the committee was
quoted as saying by the news agency, monitored in Tokyo.
   ``For the North-South top-level talks so ardently desired by the
whole nation, it is urgent to remove the legal and institutional
factors that undermine the atmosphere of national reconciliation
and trust,'' the committee said.
   South Korea's National Security Law provides penalties ranging
from five years imprisonment to death for sedition and anti-state
activity, and is used to control activities which encourage or
support North Korea.
   In a speech to the South Korean National Assembly Oct. 4, Roh
said he was willing to meet his North Korean counterpart, Kim Il
Sung, ``at any place and at the earliest possible date to discuss
any and all issues'' between the two Koreas.
   Roh did not disclose the details of his reunification proposals,
but said the new formula would be ``practicable and acceptable to
both sides.''
   Korea was divided at the end of World War II into the communist
North and capitalist South. They fought against each other in the
1950-53 Korean War and remain staunch enemies.
</TEXT>
