<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--NuclearWake-Up     10-15 0133</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Nuclear Wake-Up,0137</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Gets Early Morning Wake-Up Call</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNT LEBANON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of this Pittsburgh suburb
got an unexpected wake-up call when a siren normally reserved for a
nuclear attack was accidentally activated.
   But only about 30 people out of the town's population of about
34,400 called authorities to find out what was going on, said Fire
Chief Steve Walther.
   Walther said the siren, atop the Mount Lebanon Municipal
Building, was accidentally set off shortly before 5:30 a.m. Friday.
   The siren is designed to sound the up-and-down wail to warn of
an impending nuclear attack, Walther said. In a local emergency,
the siren would sound a continuous drone.
   Walther said the siren sounded for about three minutes, as
programmed.
   ``We also learned our cancel button doesn't work,'' he said.
