<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--China-Corruption     10-15 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--China-Corruption,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Major Chinese Corporation Trimmed in Anti-Corruption Drive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government ordered a major Chinese
corporation linked to official corruption to consolidate and sever
ties with a welfare fund headed by the son of senior leader Deng
Xiaoping, an official report said today.
   The state-run investment and development firm, Kang Hua
Development Corp., is reported to be a main target of a government
campaign against the pervasive problem of official corruption. The
corporation says it controls about 200 companies nationwide.
   The People's Daily newspaper said Deng singled out the company
for criticism. It said he ordered it to cut ties with the China
Welfare Fund for the Handicapped, which is run by his disabled son,
Deng Pufang.
   Unconfirmed reports in the Hong Kong press have said Kang Hua
officials used links to the welfare fund to obtain tax privileges
and extra import permits. Reports have charged that the company has
profiteered in imports and other hard-to-get materials.
</TEXT>
