<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis     10-15 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Jokes At Jackson Birthday Party; Woos Hispanic Vote</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: First event scheduled for 10:30 a.m. EDT; lede planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis early today attended a
birthday tribute to Jesse Jackson, saluting his former rival's work
on behalf of the Democratic Party while joking about a flap that
jeopardized their relationship.
   The Democratic presidential nominee also trumpeted his candidacy
at the Los Angeles gathering and was given a glowing endorsement by
Jackson.
   Dukakis was picking up the endorsement of a Hispanic police
group today in Los Angeles before flying on to San Antonio, Texas
and then home to Boston.
   The Jackson event came at the end of a marathon campaign day for
Dukakis, who appeared with Jackson on Friday morning in Los
Angeles, hours later with running mate Lloyd Bentsen in Sacramento,
at an early evening rally in Seattle and a meeting of a Hispanic
organization back in Los Angeles just before attending the Jackson
party.
   At each of the stops he raised an issue that came up during his
final debate with Republican nominee George Bush on Thursday _ the
appointments the next president will get to make to the Supreme
Court.
   Dukakis told the crowds that Bush would appoint people like
Robert Bork, an appointee of President Reagan who was rejected by
the Senate, while he would appoint justices dedicated to civil and
voters' rights.
   Joint appearances between Dukakis and Jackson have been rare
since the Democratic National Convention and Dukakis, attempting a
series of jokes during his address at the birthday party, created
an awkward moment when he joked that he had not known about the
party until told by reporters.
   ``Don't you think he'd have called me,'' Dukakis said, his joke
met by polite but nervous laughter.
   When Dukakis selected Bentsen, he was unable to reach Jackson
and the former candidate was told of the selection by reporters,
sparking a temporary rift between the two.
   Dukakis also turned questions about his personality into jokes
about the exuberant Jackson.
   ``Jesse, you've got to smile more,'' Dukakis said. ``We've got
to make him a little more likeable, don't you think?''
   Dukakis came bearing gifts, giving Jackson a video cassette
recorder, a Dukakis-Bentsen hat and a Dukakis campaign jacket.
   In return, Jackson delivered an impassioned endorsement of his
former rival.
   ``The governor set the pace, established the principles,
articulated the policies, set forth the priorities,'' Jackson said.
``Now we the people must make the investment.''
   Jackson said that a Bush administration would threaten civil
rights gains and declared:
   ``Governor Dukakis can be trusted to keep hope alive and build
the America that must be, the America of our dreams.''
   Earlier, at the Hispanic event, Dukakis continued his
post-debate attempt to paint Bush as a failed leader who
demonstrated his lack of judgment in selecting Indiana Sen. Dan
Quayle as his running mate and by saying during the debate that
Bork would have been an ``outstanding'' justice.
   He mockingly referred to Bush's pledge to put Quayle in charge
of the war on drugs.
   ``Ladies and gentlemen, we can't take four years of that _ we
can't take four days of that,'' Dukakis said.
   He also defended himself against Bush charges that Dukakis is
soft on crime, referring to crimes committed against his father and
brother and the decline in major crimes during his tenure as
Massachusetts governor.
   ``I just didn't decide to care in an election year,'' Dukakis
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
