<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lite     10-15 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lite,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For a while it looked like Chicken Boy, who
had been perched atop a fast-food restaurant for 16 years, wouldn't
get any respect.
   The 22-foot-tall, 500 pound half-man, half-chicken statue was
rejected by the Museum of Contemporary Art in Los Angeles, the
Museum of Modern Mythology in San Francisco and even the
Smithsonian Institution.
   But graphics designer Amy Inouye decided to save the Los Angeles
landmark from oblivion. She bought the fiberglass statue from the
eatery for $1,500 in 1985, and would not let rejection ruffle her
feathers.
   She decided to turn Chicken Boy into a golden goose.
   Last year, she created the ``Chicken Boy Catalog for a Perfect
World,'' filled with a line of gifts inspired by the statue, which
has the head of a cartoon hen and the body of a muscle man holding
a yellow bucket of chicken.
   ``Chicken Boy always really meant something to me,'' said Ms.
Inouye. ``He kind of symbolizes Los Angeles. I think he's odd and
goofy, and also kind of serene, which is something I admire.''
   The catalog offers T-shirts, postcards, mugs, watches, ball
point pens _ even boxer shorts _ all bearing Chicken Boy's
likeness. Many items include his motto, ``Too Tall to Live, Too
Weird to Die.''
   The catalog also features such novelties as Goodyear Tire
ashtrays, Lava Lites, and Ms. Inouye's own creation, ``computer
cozies,'' computer covers that come in Hawaiian or leopard prints.
   Chicken Boy so far hasn't generated the kind of consumer
interest of Garfield or the Smurfs, but Ms. Inouye says she has
sold about 2,000 T-shirts and has managed to turn a small profit.
   ``There really hasn't been a plan behind all this. I look at it
more as a learning experience,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
