<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NewspaperFire     10-15 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Newspaper Fire,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>San Diego Newspaper Evacuated After Fire Breaks Out In Pressroom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flames leaped up to 10 feet in the air and
smoke filled the pressroom of the San Diego Union & Tribune
building early today when a fire broke out in one of four presses
printing The San Diego Union.
   Approximately 150 to 200 people evacuated the building after the
fire broke out at 1:15 a.m. No one was injured, and the blaze was
extinguished within minutes by the newspaper's fire sprinkler
system. Employees were allowed to return a little more than an hour
later.
   There was no structural damage to the building, but smoke and
water damage was extensive, said Battalion Chief Russell Loughy of
the San Diego Fire Department. It wasn't immediately known how
badly the press was damaged, he said.
   The cause of the fire was under investigation.
   Workers putting out an early edition of the morning Union were
alerted to the fire when a loud alarm went off.
   ``And then we saw smoke fill the entire pressroom,'' said John
Barksdale, a plate maker. ``There were flames on the press and
paper.''
</TEXT>
