<HEAD>Teen-Ager Indicted For Murder In Death That Sparked Riot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHREVEPORT, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grand jury indicted a white teen-ager
on second-degree murder charges in connection with the shooting of
a black man whose death triggered rioting in a mostly black
neighborhood last month.
   Tamala ``Tami'' Vergo, 17, of Greenwood faces a maximum penalty
of life in prison if convicted in the killing of William McKinney,
22. She was indicted Thursday.
   Police said the Sept. 20 shooting stemmed from a drug deal that
went sour, but that McKinney was only a bystander.
   Officials have blamed the rioting in the Cedar Grove
neighborhood on a buildup of racial tension in the black community
from several factors, including unemployment.
   Cynthia Johnson, who was not indicted in the case, told police
she drove Ms. Vergo to a convenience store parking lot to buy
``crack'' cocaine.
   Police said there was a confrontation at the site, and Ms. Vergo
allegedly fired two indiscriminate shots toward a group of people
nearby. One bullet struck McKinney, who was not involved in the
dispute.
   Defense attorney Maurice Loridans has indicated his defense of
Ms. Vergo will include self-protection.
