<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Taiwan-Pollution     10-15 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan-Pollution,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protesting Fishermen Accept $20 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fishermen protesting chemical pollution
agreed today to accept more than $20 million to end a sit-in that
halted work at 18 factories in a major petrochemical complex, a
government official said.
   About 2,000 fishermen stormed the Linyuan Industrial Park, about
220 miles south of Taipei, on Wednesday. They claim polluted
wastewater from the factories has poisoned fish and shrimp in their
fishing grounds.
   They originally demanded a total of $26.3 million, or about
$3,500 for each of the 7,500 members of their nearby village,
Sanwei.
   However, Yang Shih-chien, head of the Industrial Development
Bureau, said the fishermen instead agreed to a total of $20.7
million, or about $2,800 for each resident. The government and
factories will share the cost.
   The official told reporters that operation of the complex would
resume soon, possibly by Sunday or Monday.
   Government officials will continue to negotiate with residents
in other villages affected by the pollution, he said.
   Meanwhile, Economics Minister Chen Li-an told legislators his
ministry would tighten pollution controls at the complex within
three years.
   The affected companies include two that account for about 60
percent of the ethylene, propylene and other chemical materials
supplied to Taiwan's export-oriented textile and plastic industries.
</TEXT>
