^Where There's Smokes, There's Debates</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southern California is well known for its
fitness-oriented culture, but reporters who came to cover this
week's presidential debate were greeted by one bit of hospitality
that did not quite fit in with the health-conscious stereotype.
   In the UCLA ballroom where a press working area was set up,
media representatives were treated to all the free cigarettes they
could smoke.
   The tables piled with cigarette packs came courtesy of the
Philip Morris company _ as did the full buffet of cold cuts, hot
dishes, salads and desserts.
   It wasn't the first time those covering the debates were treated
by the cigarette manufacturer.
   The traveling press hospitality center has followed the
election-year debate schedule from the heart of tobacco land in
Winston-Salem, N.C., where the first Michael Dukakis-George Bush
debate was held, to Omaha, Neb., for last week's vice presidential
debate, and on to Los Angeles for the last presidential showdown.
   And there was a specific reason for the omnipresence of Philip
Morris, even though some non-smoking members of the media
complained that the dispensing of free cigarettes only encouraged
puffing by smokers who have learned to curtail their habit aboard
campaign planes.
   Philip Morris was one of the three top financial backers of the
trio of debates, said Janet Brown, director of the bipartisan
Commission on Presidential Debates that hosted the events.
   She did not disclose the amount of Philip Morris' contribution,
but said it was in the six-figure range. The cost of putting on
each debate was estimated at some $500,000, which had to be raised
by the commission from corporate, private and other sources.
   It was Philip Morris' request to contribute to the debate by
fully outfitting the press center at each one, she said.
   As for the cigarettes, ``They simply said they'd like to put out
a range of their products including cigarettes.`
   Other Philip Morris-owned products on hand included Jell-O
pudding, in addition to free pens, notebooks and ashtrays.
   Philip Morris is also a major contributor to the Democratic
Party, giving the Democratic National Committee at least $100,000
this year.
</TEXT>
