<2ND_LINE>PM-Paramedic Sentenced, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0436,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paramedic Who Refused To Treat Man Sentenced To Jail</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Wagner, who ...' to CORRECT Wagner to
Dougherty.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Fire Department paramedic was
sentenced to a year in jail for refusing to aid a disabled
alcoholic who died, partly from lack of treatment.
   Superior Court Judge J.D. Smith told retired paramedic Robert
Dougherty, 50, on Friday that he had an arrogant attitude at work
that contributed to the death of 42-year-old Melvin Wagner.
   The prosecutor, Deputy District Attorney Brian Kelberg, said
Dougherty ``had a long history of deciding outside the scope of his
responsibilities who should or shouldn't get care.''
   Dougherty, a 20-year department veteran, also was sentenced to
three years' probation for admitting to submitting false
information on a report about the handling of Wagner.
   Dougherty, who retired in 1987, pleaded guilty in July to gross
negligence in Wagner's death on Sept. 23, 1985.
   Dougherty refused to heed Wagner's pleas to be taken to a
hospital after Wagner said he had been ill for four months, the
paramedic's partner, James Mihalka, testified. Dougherty termed the
case a transportation problem and left without taking the vital
signs of the partially paralyzed man.
   On a second call to Wagner's residential hotel, Dougherty
refused to enter Wagner's room, even though a social worker said
the man was gasping for breath, Mihalka said.
   Wagner died a little more than an hour after the paramedics'
second visit. A coroner determined that Wagner died of internal
hemorrhaging.
</TEXT>
