<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChristianCenterDeath     10-15 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Christian Center Death,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Staff Member Charged with Murdering Daughter of Center's Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos PD1,3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. CRUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANDY, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A staff member at a Christian center was
charged with killing the 8-year-old daughter of the center's fiery
leader, and 53 other children who may have been abused were taken
into custody, authorities said.
   Dayna Lorea Broussard, 8, had been beaten and whipped to death,
Dr. Larry Lewman, Oregon's medical examiner, said Friday.
   The girl apparently lived at one of two homes outside Portland
occupied by children and others affiliated with the Los
Angeles-based Watts Christian Center. Her father, Eldridge
Broussard Jr., is pastor at the center.
   A staff member at the center, Willie K. Chambers, was charged
with murder. Chambers, 35, also is the father of a student at the
center.
   Carolyn Van Brunt, dean of the school and training programs at
Watts Christian Center, said the group sometimes used ``physical
correction'' as a form of discipline. Speaking Friday night from
Los Angeles, she denied the punishment was cruel, but said she had
never seen it administered.
   ``These kids are from (the Los Angeles ghetto) Watts and they
have to deal with gangs and drugs and people with no discipline,''
she said.
   Chambers and three other adults brought the girl's body to a
fire station in a rural area southeast of Portland early Friday.
The other three were charged with hindering prosecution.
   Clackamas County sheriff's Capt. Pat Detloff said deputies then
went to one of the center's homes about eight miles east of Sandy
and 25 miles east of Portland.
   There, they found three adults supervising 29 boys and 24 girls,
ranging in age between 3 months and 16 years, Detloff said.
   There was little furniture in the house and the children
appeared to be sleeping on pillows on the floor, he said.
Investigators were unsure how long the children had been at the
home, he added.
   Authorities ``noticed some of the kids appeared to have old
injuries that would be suspected as physical abuse,'' Detloff said.
The three adult supervisors were not charged, he added.
   Most of the children were taken by bus Friday night to juvenile
shelters in Woodburn and Salem, while others were placed
temporarily in foster homes, said Alice Galloway of the state
Children's Services Division.
   Galloway said physical examinations and interviews were planned
over the weekend for the children, all of whom are from Los Angeles.
   ``We hope to have them back with their parents as soon as
possible,'' she said.
</TEXT>
