<DOCNO> AP881015-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-88 0818EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Colombia     10-15 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Colombia,0635</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Leading Political Parties Agree On Constitutional Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombia's Liberal and Conservative
parties have agreed to reform the country's constitution, and a
court system that will not let drug traffickers go unpunished
appears to be one of the goals.
   Other proposed changes would allow the bicarmel legislature to
force Cabinet ministers to resign and allow presidential primary
elections.
   The amended constitution also would end 28 years of each
president being required to name some Cabinet ministers from the
opposition party.
   The agreement, disclosed Friday by Colombia's minister of
government, Cesar Gaviria, ended two years of bitter feuding
between the two parties on what changes there should be in the
constitution.
   President Virgilio Barco of the Liberal Party met for eight
hours with former president Julio Cesar Turbay, director of the
Liberal Party, and former president Misael Pastrana, chief of the
Conservative party, Gaviria said.
   The Colombian Congress will be asked to approve the
constitutional reforms before it goes into recess Dec. 17, Gaviria
said at a news conference. The Liberal and Conservative parties
make up 95 percent of Colombia's congress.
   A bipartisan congressional committee appointed earlier this year
to study possible reforms decided that Colombia's court system
should be patterned in some ways after the U.S. court system.
   The current 19th-centry court system in Colombia has judges
investigating cases, taking depositions, hearing out of court
testimony and deciding on their own if a suspect should be charged
or set free.
   It is common knowledge that some judges are bribed. No major
drug trafficker has ever been convicted of drug trafficking and
spent more than a few weeks in jail.
   Currently federal prosecutors play a very small role in
Colombia. Criminal charges are made by individuals, and a chief
judge assigns investigations to other judges. Under the new system,
a federal prosecutor would decide who would be charged and would
take over the investigatory duties.
   The constitutional reform committee also envisions the naming of
a special prosecutor to be in charge of human rights cases.
   Death squads have killed more than 800 people in the last two
years. Each of those cases is investigated by a different judge,
denying the possibility of a major federal investigation linking
any of the cases.
   There have been only 12 convictions in death squad cases.
   The minister of government said Friday that the constitutional
reforms would allow Colombia's Congress to force a Cabinet minister
to resign.
   Currently Colombia's congress has little power. Constitutional
reform would allow the congress to censure a Cabinet minister on a
vote of confidence.
   Another major change in Colombian politics would be the end of
Colombia's National Front, a sharing of power between the Liberal
and Conservative parties. The National Front was created 28 years
ago to end a war between the Liberal and Conservative parties, a
war that took more than 250,000 lives.
   The two parties had decided then to alternate the presidency
every four years, with no president being able to succeed himself.
   The National Front agreement also requires each president to
name some Cabinet ministers from the opposition party. The number
appointed depends upon the percentage of votes the opposition
received in the presidential election. The Conservative Party
withdrew from the Front after Barco was elected in 1986. The two
party leaders also agreed the constitition should allow each party
to decide before each presidential election if there should be a
primary election, Gaviria said.
   Under the bill to be presented to congress, future changes in
the constitution could be proposed by the president and put to a
national vote, the minister of government said. Now only the
congress can amend the constitution.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881015-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-88 0907EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Mandela     10-15 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Mandela,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mrs. Mandela Visits Husband, Says He Is Angered By Botha</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Winnie Mandela visited her
husband, black nationalist Nelson Mandela, at his tightly guarded
hospital room today and said he was angry at suggestions he was
cooperating with the government.
   President P.W. Botha, while in Switzerland last week, suggested
the jailed African National Congress leader could be freed if he
``continues cooperating with the authorities, as he is doing at
present.''
   ``About the so-called cooperation with the government, Mandela
says he will answer to that himself,'' Mrs. Mandela told reporters.
``As he said that, he looked very angry.''
   Mandela, 70, is recuperating from tuberculosis at the
Constantiaberg Clinic, a modern private hospital in Cape Town. He
became ill in August, and doctors expect him to make a complete
recovery in two to three months.
   Mrs. Mandela said she and her husband did not discuss the latest
wave of speculation that he may soon be freed after 26 years in
prison.
   ``All the rumors about his release are sheer rumors,'' she said.
   In addition to his wife, Mandela was visited for more than an
hour by his daughter, Zindzi, and her two children, as well as by
his sister, Leaby Piliso. It was the Mandelas' first reunion since
August.
   Mrs. Mandela declined to comment on political issues but said
her husband's health was improving.
   Botha, although refusing to be specific, has said in recent
weeks that he hopes Mandela will not have to return to Pollsmoor
Prison from the hospital. Government officials have indicated
Mandela might be freed without having to comply with Botha's
longstanding demand that he renounce violence.
   Mandela has been jailed since 1962. He received a life sentence
in 1964 for plotting an ANC sabotage campaign aimed at toppling the
white-minority government.
   President Mobutu Sese Seko of Zaire said after meeting with
Botha on Oct. 1 that the South African president had promised to
release Mandela unconditionally. Botha refused to confirm this, but
a pro-government newspaper, The Citizen, subsequently quoted
officials as saying Mandela could be released at any time starting
in mid-November.
   Mandela is the most popular leader among South Africa's
disenfranchised black majority. Government officials are wary that
his release could cause a new outbreak of black militancy and
unrest, but they also perceive that freeing Mandela could ease
international pressure on South Africa.
   In other developments:
   _An explosion early today outside a police barracks in
Kathlehong, a black township near Johannesburg, caused damage but
no injuries. The blast came 10 hours after a limpet mine exploded
at a Johannesburg bus depot, injuring four people. Most of the
roughly 80 bombings in South Africa this year have been blamed by
police on the African National Congress.
   _Govan Mbeki, 78, an ANC leader freed last year after 23 years
in prison, lost a court bid Friday to overturn restrictions placed
on him after his release. The activist, a co-defendant of
Mandela's, had challenged the legality of the emergency regulations
under which his restrictions were imposed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
