<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Kurds 1stLd-Writethru a0430 10-15 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kurds, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0430,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Reportedly Closes Border to Kurdish Refugees</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with new IRNA report on Kurds. No
pickup.
^By ZEYNEP ALEMDAR</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran has closed its border to Kurdish
refugees fleeing Iraq through Turkey, a Turkish official said. Iran
said today that accepting more Kurdish refugees would be a problem.
   Regional Gov. Hayri Kozakcioglu said Friday that Iran took in
2,178 Kurdish refugees from Turkey one month ago but then closed
its border.
   Kozakcioglu said 3,000 Kurdish refugees were taken this week in
buses and trucks from two tent cities in southeast Turkey to Alan,
a village on the Iranian border. But the Iranians refused to accept
the refugees, he said, and after a two-day wait at the border they
were taken back to the tent cities.
   Turkish news agencies say up to 19,000 Kurdish refugees have
voluntarily transferred to Iran.
   Iran's deputy prime minister, Ali-Reza Moayeri, was quoted today
by Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency as saying: ``Due to
early cold weather in the western border regions, the arrival of
fresh groups of Kurds will be difficult and dangerous.''
   Iran had offered to accept any of the 60,000 Kurdish refugees
who poured into Turkey starting in late August, after Iraq began an
offensive against the ethnic minority. The Kurds claim Iraq used
chemical weapons against them.
   Moayeri was quoted as saying Iran has accepted 100,000 Kurdish
refugees fleeing Iraq since an Aug. 20 cease-fire in the 8-year-old
Iran-Iraq war. The Tehran government backed Kurdish separatists in
Iraq during the fighting.
   Taking more refugees will entail more problems for the refugees
and for Iran, Moayeri was quoted as saying by IRNA, monitored in
Nicosia, Cyprus.
   IRNA said Thursday that 32,000 Kurdish refugees from Turkey have
sought sanctuary in northwest Iran, including nearly 8,000 the last
few days, because of Ankara's ``reluctance to host them.''
   Kozakcioglu denied the report, saying ``such a legal transfer
was impossible as long as Iran kept its border closed.''
   But he said Turkey would not be able to control illegal
crossings into Iran because of the rough border terrain.
   Last week, 1,467 Kurds returned voluntarily from Turkey to Iraq,
which has offered an amnesty to those who fled. The rest of the
Kurdish refugees are settled in five tent cities in southeastern
Turkey.
</TEXT>
