<HEAD>Israeli Attacked with Knives and Axes in West Bank City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assailants armed with axes and knives today
attacked an Israeli man on a business trip in the occupied West
Bank, the army said. The assault came after Israeli troops raided
three nearby villages.
   The 56-year-old businessman, whose name was not disclosed, was
rushed to the surgery ward of Afula hosptial suffering deep gashes
in his head, neck and back, the spokesman said on condition of
anonymity.
   Soldiers closed off access to Jenin, where the attack occurred,
and began searching for the assailants, who managed to steal their
victim's pistol before escaping, the spokesman said. The troops
made several arrests.
   In another incident, Palestinians threw stones at an Israel-Arab
couple visiting Jenin, the army said.
   Hours earlier, police and soldiers staged a nighttime raid on
the villages of Jalbun, Faqqua and Arabuna, near Jenin, Israel
radio reported.
   The security forces found a large cache of explosives, timers
and batteries used to manufacture bombs, the radio said.
   They arrested 20 Palestinians suspected of setting fire to
trees, blocking roads, hoisting outlawed Palestinian flags and
participating in disturbances. The radio said the West Bank
Palestinians operated inside Israel.
   Also today, soldiers opened fire with plastic bullets in Rafah,
the southernmost town in the occupied Gaza Strip, wounding two
Palestinians during a stone-throwing demonstration, the army
command said. Both Palestinians were shot in the leg and taken to
hospital in Khan Yunis.
   Israeli officials estimate that 7,000 Arabs have been wounded in
the occupied territories since the Palestinian uprising began Dec.
8. Palestinian sources put the number at about 18,000. At least 297
Palestinians and six Israelis have died during the uprising.
