<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Canada-Indians 1stLd-Writethru a0473 10-15 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-Indians, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0473,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indians Block Bridge To U.S. In Dispute Over Reservation Raid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 1 graf for 4th graf pvs, ``The police...'' to ADD that
raid carried out by Canadian police. Pickup 5th graf pvs, ``Seven
people...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CORNWALL ISLAND, Ontario (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mohawk Indians briefly blocked
the Seaway International Bridge to the United States to protest a
police raid on suspected drug and cigarette smugglers in the
Akwesasne Indian Reserve.
   The Indians used their cars Friday night to block the bridge for
about 10 minutes in both directions and nailed a sign to an
immigration booth that read: ``This is Indian land _ Mohawk land.
No trespassing.''
   The bridge connects Cornwall Island in the St. Lawrence Seaway
with mainland Canada to the north and New York to the south. The
reserve, where 100,000 Indians live, is located on the island.
   The raid was carried out Thursday by 250 heavily armed Canadian
police with 75 cruisers, 15 vans, unmarked cars, helicopters,
boats, bulldozers and dogs trained to sniff out illegal drugs.
   Seven people were arrested and large quantities of illegal
cigarettes, some drugs and weapons worth $200,000 were seized,
police said. The raid was one of the largest in the 18-month
attempt to stop Mohawk Indians from bringing duty-free cigarettes
from the United States for resale in Canada.
   Some Indians called for retaliation. ``We were raped,'' said
Francis Boot, a bus driver whose home was one of 12 raided on the
island. ``It was no different than if the (U.S.) 7th Cavalry had
come across and attacked us.''
   Boots scoffed at the police description of what was seized,
describing it instead as ``some cigarettes and a couple of useless
pistols.'' But police said their search turned up restricted
weapons, marijuana and cocaine.
   Mohawk Grand Chief Mike Mitchell appealed for calm among his
people, but Boots said he and others have contacted ``our brothers
and sisters in New York and Montreal'' to join in meetings to
discuss a unified reaction to the raid.
   The raid was similar to one in May in the Kahnawake Reserve just
south of Montreal in which 17 people were arrested for selling
illegal cigarettes.
</TEXT>
