<HEAD>Rains Damage Cropfields, Kill Two Fishermen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tropical storm destroyed 80 homes in
a Vietnamese province, damaged tens of thousands of acres of crops
and killed two fishermen whose boat capsized, Vietnamese radio said
Saturday.
   Initial reports said constant, heavy rains from Tuesday to
Friday damaged 172,970 acres of newly planted corn, potato and rice
fields in central province of Nghe Tinh, the Voice of Vietnam said.
Up to 19.7 inches fell in some places.
   ``The accompanying whirlwinds pulled down some 80 dwelling
houses and capsized two fishing boats, killing two fishermen,''
said the broadcast, monitored in Bangkok.
   An earlier domestic Radio Hanoi broadcast said heavy rains
caused flash floods in other provinces in recent days, damaging
rice fields, roads and rail lines.
   Tropical storms annually cause considerable damage to the
Vietnamese economy.
