<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Kurds     10-15 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Kurds,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Will Not Accept More Kurdish Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran has accepted 100,000 Kurdish
refugees fleeing from Iraq, and accepting more would be a problem,
an Iranian official was quoted Saturday as saying.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency quoted Ali-Reza
Moayeri, deputy prime minister, as saying, ``Due to early cold
weather in the western border regions, the arrival of fresh groups
of Kurds will be difficult and dangerous.''
   A Kurdish spokesman said Thursday that Turkey has forced 30,000
Kurds into Iran last week, where they were crammed into overcrowded
camps.
   Moayeri spent Friday in Turkey discussing the refugee problem
with Prime Minister Turgut Ozal, Foreign Minister Mesut Yilmaz and
other government officials, said IRNA, monitored in Nicosia. It
said Moayeri described the talks as friendly.
   A Turkish offical said Friday that Iran closed its border with
Turkey to prevent any more crossings by Kurdish refugees who fled
Iraq during an army offensive against them. The Kurds said they
were fleeing chemical bomb attacks.
   Regional Gov. Hayri Kozakcioglu said that Iran received 2,178
Kurdish refugees from Turkey a month ago but then closed its border
to the refugees, saying it had no shelter for them.
   Iraq started its offensive against the Kurds in August, soon
after Iran agreed to the cease-fire in the 8-year-old Iran-Iran
war. The Kurds, who are seeking autonomy for their region, sided
with Iran during the war.
   Moyaeri criticized the world reaction to the Kurdish claims of
chemical bomb attacks.
   ``Unfortunately the world has not shown a proper reaction to the
Iraqi atrocities against the Kurds,'' he said. ``Neither Iran nor
Turkey have received aid for the Kurdish refugees.''
   Taking more refugees will entail more problems for the refugees
and for Iran, Moayeri said. He said both countries will try to work
for improved existing conditions for the refugees.
   About 20 million Kurds live in the mountainous region where the
borders of Turkey, Iran and Iraq converge. They have fought
periodically in all three countries for more than 80 years for
autonomy.
</TEXT>
