<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghan-Soviet     10-15 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan-Soviet,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Ambassador Arrives In Kabul, Indication Of Desire For Close
Ties</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Kabul Mood, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Asssociated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Soviet diplomat arrived in
Kabul on Saturday to take up his post as ambassador in an
indication of Moscow's desire to retain a strong influence over its
southern neighbor.
   A Soviet Embassy official said First Deputy Foreign Minister
Yuli Vorontsov would present his credentials to the Afghan
government within three days.
   He spoke on condition of anonymity and said he was unable to
give any details of Vorontsov's schedule.
   Vorontsov has worked closely with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze, who in turn is close to President Mikhail Gorbachev.
Such senior Kremlin officials rarely double as foreign ambassadors.
   The change coincides with a stepped-up Soviet and Afghan
campaign for a negotiated end to the fighting that has pitted
Afghan and Soviet troops against U.S.- and Pakistan-backed Moslem
guerrillas.
   Last week, the Soviet Union pledged $800 million to the U.N.
fund for rebuilding Afghanistan _ nearly half the $2 billion the
United Nations says is needed in the next five years.
   Moscow Radio's English-language program heard in Kabul on
Saturday noted that the Soviet Union had pledged such a large sum
while, according to the broadcast, the United States was slow to
respond with a similar amount.
   An expected meeting of the Central Committee of the People's
Democratic Party of Afghanistan has prompted speculation among both
Western and non-Western diplomats that a change in party leadership
may be forthcoming.
   President Najib heads the Afghan government and is also
secretary-general of the party.
   A veteran, non-Western diplomat said he doubted the Soviet Union
would want to see a new Afghan president until the Red Army's
withdrawal is completed.
   ``Why should they want the government to change before they get
their children home?'' he asked.
   Under the U.N.-mediated agreement worked out in April in Geneva,
the Soviet Union is to complete the withdrawal of its troops by
Feb. 15, 1989. The withdrawal started May 15 and is now half over,
with an estimated 50,000 to 60,000 Soviet soldiers remaining in
Afghanistan.
   The Soviet Union intervened in Afghanistan in December 1979.
</TEXT>
