<DOCNO> AP881015-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-88 1110EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush-FinalWeeks Bjt   10-15 0755</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Final Weeks, Bjt,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush to Stick to Proven Themes, Big States in Final Weeks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, riding the momentum of last
week's debate, will focus on proven themes and big states as he
tries to hold or expand his lead in the final three weeks of the
presidential campaign, aides say.
   They say he will not stray far from the themes he has already
honed on the campaign trail _ crime, the death penalty, prison
furloughs in Massachusetts, a strong military _ and will break
little if any new ground on issues.
   Although Bush is enjoying a widening lead in public opinion
polls over Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis, he and
his top campaign officials are insisting they will not permit
themselves to become complacent.
   ``That's the last thing I want to have happen,'' Bush said at
week's end as it became clear his campaign was enjoying a
post-debate surge.
   While maintaining a busy schedule, Bush can be expected to run a
cautious, play-it-safe campaign in the days ahead.
   That means sticking to his basic campaign stump speech, speaking
mostly before friendly audiences, having few news conferences and
seldom departing from a well-rehearsed script.
   Bush himself told reporters, ``I don't feel any pressure to put
out a lot of new programs'' at this stage in the campaign. ``We've
got a lot of programs out there.''
   He conceded that ``you'll see a lot of similarity'' in his
campaign speeches in the next three weeks with the tried-and-tested
themes he's been hammering on since the Republican convention last
August.
   Above all, Bush as well as his top advisers are saying they will
take nothing for granted.
   Asked by reporters how he assessed the debate, he said at one
point, ``Read my smile.''
   But he also said, ``You're talking to a guy who, when the polls
were going the other way, said `it isn't over.' And it wasn't. So
why should I now suddenly have the luxury of changing my position?''
   ``Watch how hard we work,'' Bush said, echoing the sentiment of
his campaign chairman, James A. Baker III, who cautioned senior
aides on Friday to _ above all else _ avoid becoming cocky or
viewing a Bush election as inevitable.
   ``There's a 100 percent chance of getting into trouble if you
get smug and overconfident,'' added campaign manager Lee Atwater.
``We don't intend to do that.''
   Bush in the coming days will travel mostly to large states where
polls show the election remains close.
   After leaving California, where he has been since last Tuesday
and where the stakes may be the highest in the country, Bush plans
campaign visits in pivotal Midwestern states.
   Aides also said Bush plans to keep returning to New Jersey and
will even spend some time campaigning in New York _ where recent
polls suggest the state's 36 electoral votes may be within striking
distance, despite a wide early lead by Dukakis.
   ``We're going to concentrate on the Electoral College _
California, New York, Ohio, Illinois, New Jersey,'' Atwater said.
``The vice president's base is secure in the South and the West.''
   Bill Lacy, Bush's California coordinator, said the vice
president's performance in last Thursday's debate, which generally
got high marks from Americans responding to a variety of surveys,
will help in California.
   Still, the state, with its rich bounty of 47 electoral votes, is
still up for grabs, Lacy said in an interview.
   He noted that Bush at one point last summer had been as much as
18 points behind in California. But he said, ``Polls in the last
few weeks have shown it to be a very close race so we're going to
keep pressing and keep pushing as hard as we can.''
   Bush will also be courting the ``Reagan Democrats,''
traditionally Democratic voters _ many of them blue-collar workers
_ who bolted in 1980 and 1984 to vote for President Reagan.
   Early polls showed many of these Democrats were not ready to
give the same support to Bush but more recent surveys suggest some
are moving in that direction.
   Bush will spend most of this week in the Midwest, and much of
the campaigning, particularly in industrial areas, will be aimed at
these Reagan Democrats.
   ``They respond to issues like crime, prison furloughs, gun
control, defense, the death penalty, the nuclear freeze and the
ACLU,'' Atwater said. ``Bush needs 35 percent of the Reagan
Democrats to win the election and he's in the neighborhood of 50
percent now.''
</TEXT>
