<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-88 1112EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PickingtheLock Bjt   10-15 0898</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Picking the Lock, Bjt,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Seems to Be Failing to Unlock Bush's Hold on South, West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis' strategy of containing George
Bush's built-in campaign advantage in the South and West appears to
be crumbling rapidly as Republicans paint him as an unreconstructed
liberal, according to the polls and political experts.
   Dukakis advisers reject any talk of a GOP Electoral College
``lock'' in these reliably Republican regions. But they concede
that Bush's aggressive campaign _ television commercials included _
has forced them to scramble to remain competitive in even a
relative handful of states.
   One adviser, Charlie Baker, says the talk of a solid Republican
South is a calculated attempt by the Bush campaign to create an
impression that the race is over, and thus discourage voters from
going to the polls. ``They believe that if more people vote they
lose,'' he said.
   ``If they had a lock in the West, George Bush wouldn't be
spending two days in Colorado,'' he said, citing one example of a
close state.
   Still, polls do indicate Bush has solidified his position in the
South and West in the past few weeks. And Dukakis has clearly cut
back efforts in some states, including Florida, though maintaining
a costly effort in running mate Lloyd Bentsen's Texas as well as a
few scattered others.
   Merle Black, a political scientist at the University of North
Carolina, believes Dukakis' efforts to control the Southern damage
are doomed.
   ``I think you're going to see Bush sweep the region,'' he said
in a prediction before Thursday night's debate in which the vice
president was rated a winner.
   Depending on which side is doing the counting, Bush's built-in
advantage in the two regions runs to 100 to 170 electoral votes or
so, out of 270 needed for victory. That's a powerful foundation on
which to base his nationwide campaign, and Dukakis has nothing
comparable.
   Black said voters in the South are ``suspicious about liberals
and people who want to use the federal government to change their
lives, and George Bush has been able to capitalize.''
   In part, he said, that's the residue of racial tension from
civil rights battles. ``The more blacks there are relative to
whites, the more conservative'' the whites tend to be, he said.
   He also said Bush's strength results in part from the social
conservatism of voters in the area on issues such as gun control
and the Pledge of Allegiance.
   Says Bush Southern adviser Lanny Griffith, ``Ronald Reagan has
done a lot to leave the Sunbelt as a Republican-based region in the
presidential election. It's real important that in the first
election (after Reagan) we were able to put that together again.''
   In the West, Bush adviser Tom Hockaday says Democrats feel
``ideological differences'' with candidates on the national ticket
that cause them to vote Republican. He said Democratic governors
and senators ``tend to be more conservative'' than presidential
candidates, and issues such as water rights, gun control and the
death penalty highlight the differences between Bush and Dukakis.
   Griffith ticks off a string of campaign issues that he says the
vice president has highlighted. ``Crime, death penalty, gun
control, the furlough program (in Massachusetts), national defense,
values like prayer in public schools, the Pledge of Allegiance,
Contra aid. These are all stronger the further south you get.''
   Among the border states, he said Arkansas and Kentucky were two
where Dukakis remained competitive through late last week.
   Democrats counter that going into last week's debate, they were
ahead in Arkansas and competitive in Kentucky, Tennessee, North
Carolina and Texas. In each of those states, Dukakis is airing
television commercials beyond his national advertising.
   In several of the states, Dukakis seems to have been helped by
lingering questions about Bush's running mate Dan Quayle. Democrats
rushed to leak poll results after the vice presidential debate that
they said showed Bush's Texas margin cut from about a dozen points
to six.
   Bush has a Rocky Mountain lead, as well. Dukakis aides claim
hopes in Montana, Colorado, New Mexico and the Dakotas, but have
little or no hope in Arizona, Idaho, Wyoming, Nevada and Utah.
   A Washington Post analysis of a recent 50-state poll taken with
ABC News rated only Arkansas still a tossup among the Southern and
border states. The rest were all either rated as clear advantages
to Bush or leaning his way. The situation was similar in the Rocky
Mountain West _ Colorado and Montana were the only states not
consigned to the Bush column.
   Dukakis picked a Texan as his running mate in an attempt to gain
an instant boost in the Southern polls, and explicitly drew a
parallel to John Kennedy's selection of Texan Lyndon Johnson in his
winning 1960 campaign.
   But Republicans point to changes in voting patterns since 1960,
when Kennedy and Johnson carried Louisiana, Arkansas, Alabama,
Georgia, South Carolina and North Carolina, and 1964, when Johnson
scored a landslide.
   Since then, Democratic successes in the South have been few and
far between, highlighted by 1976, when Georgian Jimmy Carter
carried most of his native region.
   The story is similar in the West, where Democats have fared even
less well than in the South in the last quarter century. Carter
failed to carry a single state west of Texas except for Hawaii even
in his winning campaign in 1976.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
