<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-88 1130EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia     10-15 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Political Leaders Reach Agreement To Reform Constitution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombia's two major parties have agreed
to reform the constitution, proposing to stop the court system from
letting drug traffickers go unpunished.
   Another planned change would put a special prosecutor in charge
of human rights cases, clearing the way for a comprehensive
investigation of more than 800 death squad killings in the past two
years.
   The amended constitution also would allow presidential primary
elections and end 28 years of each president being required to name
some Cabinet ministers from the opposition party.
   The agreement, disclosed Friday by Colombia's minister of
government, Cesar Gaviria, ended two years of bitter feuding
between the Liberal and Conservative parties on what changes there
should be in the constitution.
   The announcement came after President Virgilio Barco of the
Liberal Party met for eight hours with former president Julio Cesar
Turbay, director of the Liberal Party, and former president Misael
Pastrana, chief of the Conservative party, Gaviria said.
   Congress will be asked to approve the constitutional reforms
before it goes into recess Dec. 17, Gaviria said at a news
conference. The Liberal and Conservative parties make up 95 percent
of Congress.
   A bipartisan congressional committee appointed this year to
study possible reforms decided that Colombia's court system should
be patterned in some ways after the U.S. system.
   Colombia's court system now lets judges investigate cases, take
depositions, hear out of court testimony and decide on their own if
a suspect should be charged or set free.
   It is common knowledge that some judges are bribed. No major
drug trafficker has ever been convicted of drug trafficking and
spent more than a few weeks in jail.
   Federal prosecutors now play a very small role in Colombia.
Criminal charges are made by individuals, and a chief judge assigns
investigations to other judges. Under the new system, a federal
prosecutor would decide who would be charged and would take over
the investigatory duties.
   The constitutional reform committee also envisions a special
prosecutor for human rights cases. Each of the death squad cases
now is investigated by a different judge, eliminating the
possibility of a major federal investigation linking any of the
cases.
   There have been only 12 convictions in death squad cases.
   The minister of government said Friday that the constitutional
reforms would allow Congress to force a Cabinet minister to resign.
   Congress now has little power. Constitutional reform would allow
it to censure a Cabinet minister on a vote of confidence.
   Another major change in Colombian politics would be the end of
the National Front, a sharing of power between the Liberal and
Conservative parties. The National Front was created 28 years ago
to end a war between the Liberal and Conservative parties that took
more than 250,000 lives.
   The two parties decided then to alternate the presidency every
four years, with no president being able to succeed himself. Under
the agreement, each president has had to work with Cabinet
ministers from the opposition party.
   The two party leaders also agreed the constitition should allow
each party to decide before each presidential election if there
should be a primary election, Gaviria said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
