<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Carbide     10-15 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Carbide,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Removes Judge From Bhopal Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BHOPAL, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appellate court removed the judge in
India's $3 billion civil suit against Union Carbide Corp. for the
Bhopal chemical disaster in a ruling widely seen as a major victory
for the U.S. company.
   Judge S.K. Seth of the Madhya Pradesh state appellate court
ruled Thursday that it was ``most disturbing'' that Bhopal District
Judge M.W. Deo ordered partial compensation for families of Bhopal
victims before completing the trial.
   Deo refused to comment Saturday on the ruling.
   The Danbury, Conn.-based company had requested Deo's removal
after the judge last year awarded $270 million as interim relief to
families of more than 3,100 people who died in the 1984 leak at a
pesticide plant owned by the Union Carbide's Indian subsidiary.
   ``We haven't seen the judge's order yet, so we can't comment,''
Ed Van Den Ameele, a Carbide spokesman in Danbury, said Saturday.
   More than 20,000 were injured in the world's worst chemical
disaster.
   The award was reduced in April this year to $192 million after
Union Carbide appealed the ruling, saying the court had no power to
order it to pay interim relief until responsibility for the gas
leakage is determined.
   The government filed suit against Union Carbide claiming the
disastrous gas leak at a pesticide factory Dec. 3, 1984, was caused
by negligence. Carbide maintains the leakage of poisonous methyl
isocyanate gas was due to sabotage by a disgruntled employee.
   Shambhu Singh will succeed Deo, a senior state government
official said Saturday on condition of anonymity.
   It was not immediately known if the removal of Deo will affect
the award of interim relief.
   The 2-year-old case is the world's largest-ever civil suit.
</TEXT>
