<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Peale     10-15 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peale,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mystery Haunts Show of Historic US Painter</HEAD>
<HEAD>By CARL HARTMAN</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mystery haunts the biggest show ever mounted
of the work of Raphaelle Peale, America's great still-life painter.
   What perplexes art historians is how Peale, who was born in
1774, learned to paint fruit, cheese and steak like the Dutch
masters of a century or more earlier.
   There is no evidence that Peale ever saw Dutch paintings, but
his work bears an uncanny similarity to them, albeit with an
additional glow and color.
   ``It's a puzzle,'' said Nicolai Cikovsky, Jr., curator of
American art at the National Gallery of Art where the Peale show
opens Sunday.
   Linda Bantel, director of the Pennsylvania Academy of Fine Arts,
said there were no museums in Peale's native Philadelphia during
his youth.
   Peale's father _ Charles Willson Peale, famous for portraits of
George Washington _ founded the first museum there in 1794. She
said she has no record of early Pennsylvania museums or private
collections containing any Dutch paintings.
   The elder Peale was his son's only teacher. Charles Peale
travelled in Europe, as Raphaelle never did, and painted occasional
still lifes.
   Charles Willson Peale married three times and had 17 children,
including Rembrandt Peale who inherited his father's gift for
portraits, Rubens Peale and two Titian Peales, one of whom died
young.
   All were named for famous painters, as was Raphaelle, whose
namesake is spelled Raphael. A daughter was called Angelica
Kauffmann Peale after a Swiss portraitist.
   The younger Peale generation was encouraged to do portraits. In
the days before photography, a good likeness could earn a painter
$100. Raphaelle sold some of his still lifes for $15 and accepted
services like carpenter's work in exchange for others.
   Last December a small painting by Raphaelle Peale sold at an art
auction in New York for a record $495,000.
   But there was little prestige to painting still lifes in
Raphaelle Peale's time.
   ``A tame, insipid, smooth, flat, mindless imitation of carrots _
good God, is this the end of art, is this the use of painting?''
asked Robert Haydon, an English painter.
   Peale was a disappointment to his family. He married a woman of
whom his father disapproved, fathered six children, drank and
disappeared for long periods, leaving his family in poverty. During
one period, he appeared to earn more from writing comic verse than
from painting.
   The show will remain in the nation's capital until Jan. 29. Then
it travels to Philadelphia, where it will be seen at the
Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts from Feb. 16 through April 16.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881015-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-88 1227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Goldwater Bjt   10-15 0845</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Goldwater, Bjt,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retransmitting a0487 to change category code</HEAD>
<HEAD>Goldwater: Dukakis, Bush Should Talk About Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former presidential candidate Barry Goldwater
says George Bush may have ``impugned the patriotism of Michael
Dukakis'' in a campaign he says has been so negative that ``as an
American citizen, I'm dammned concerned about where we're going.''
   He urged both Bush and Dukakis to ``quit calling each other
names'' and concentrate on important issues, such as how they would
handle the nation's huge debt and federal budget deficits.
   In an interview, Goldwater, who retired two years ago as
Arizona's senior Republican senator, said also he believes Sen.
Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, has stronger qualifications to become
president than does Bush's running mate, Sen. Dan Quayle, R-Ind.
   But Goldwater also said of Bush: ``I don't think I've known a
man in my life who comes to the chance of being president who is
better qualified.''
   He believes Bush will ``win rather big,'' carrying half or more
of the 50 states, and added: ``I think I know generally what George
Bush stands for. I'm very much for him. I think he'll make a good
president.''
   While Goldwater said he was surprised by the choice of Quayle,
he is ``very prejudiced'' in the 41-year-old senator's favor
because he has known him and his family for years and thought
Quayle did a ``superb'' job in handling a Senate Armed Services
panel on military procurement.
   Goldwater admitted that despite his closeness to Quayle, the
question of whether the Hoosier senator is equipped to be
president, should he ever be called on to do so, is an obvious one.
   He said it is an impossible question to answer and raised the
possibility that, like Harry Truman, Quayle might grow with the
job, should it become necessary.
   ``I'll admit this,'' Goldwater volunteered. ``The man running
for vice president on the Democrat ticket is, I think, a little
better equipped.''
   ``I've known him longer,'' Goldwater said of Bentsen. ``He's
been in the Senate longer. And he's bound to have picked up many
things that Quayle hasn't had a chance to pick up.''
   Goldwater, 79, said he is ready to return to Phoenix, having
just sold the Washington apartment he occupied for decades. He is
publicizing his new autobiography, ``Goldwater,'' a tartly worded
view of his life and the personalities with whom he has worked and
clashed in a career which spanned four decades.
   Goldwater, who was subjected to harshly negative campaign
advertisements during his 1964 presidential campaign against Lyndon
Johnson, made no secret of his distaste for the 1988 campaign.
   ``I don't like the campaign, from what I've seen of it and heard
of it,'' Goldwater said. ``I don't think that either man has been
talking about the issues.''
   He said this and the negative tone of the campaign has resulted
in widespread apathy, which he said may result for the first time
in history of a turn out of less than 50 percent of the nation's
registered voters.
   In last week's debate, Bush said Goldwater couldn't know what
the issues are because the press has not been reporting on them.
Goldwater had asked Quayle to ``tell George Bush to start talking
about the issues.''
   ``George took after me, asking how I could know what was going
on when I was living way out in Arizona,'' Goldwater said and
added: ``You'd be surprised at what we know out there.''
   Responding to questions, Goldwater refered to both Bush and
Dukakis and said: ``I think the whole camaign has been negative.''
   ``They both denied that, saying they had put out position
papers,'' he said. ``Nobody reads position papers.''
   `I've been giving both candidates a bad time for this negative
campaiging at a very, very important time in our history....As an
American citizen I'm just damned concerned about where we're
going.''
   Goldwater was asked about Bush's attack on Dukakis for the
governor's veto of legislation requiring all Massachusetts school
children to recite the Pledge of Allegiance.
   Calling the pledge a ``very big part of Americana,'' Goldwater
added: ``I don't think it deserved spending more than one or two
lectures on.''
   Then, referring to other aspects of the Bush attack, Goldwater
said the GOP candidate ``talked about the dirt in the harbors in
Massachusetts, the fact that Dukakis has given leave to convicted
murderers.''
   ``That's not going to bother the guy out in Timbuktu,'' he said.
``That guy wants to know how the hell are we going to get out of
debt.''
   He said he was not able to respond with certainty to the
question of whether Bush has impugned the integrity of Michael
Dukakis.
   But after a pause, he added: ``I have a hunch that he probably
has.''
   What does that say about the shape of American presidential
politics?
   ``Bad shape,'' Goldwater replied. ``It doesn't speak well for
the political system. The American people do not like negative
advertising or negative campaigning. They'd like to be told what's
on these fellows' minds about how to get the country in order.''
</TEXT>
