<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-88 1251EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-FinalWeeks Bjt   10-15 0783</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Final Weeks, Bjt,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With Three Weeks to Go, Trailing Dukakis Seeks Comeback Message</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time is running short for Michael Dukakis,
and the Democratic presidential nominee still is searching for a
message that will attract voters in his faltering battle against
Republican George Bush.
   With just over three weeks left until Election Day, Dukakis was
trailing in the polls and Bush appeared to have gained ground in
the final pesidential campaign debate.
   ``One of the things I have to do, obviously, is give people a
better sense of who Mike Dukakis is,'' the candidate told reporters
on his campaign plane Friday.
   It seemed a remarkable admission from a politician who has been
campaigning for president for the past 18 months.
   ``I'm expecting to win,'' he said. ``But I think it's going to
be very tight and I've always felt that way.''
   There were large signs and small that the campaign was
feverishly looking for a way to turn the tide.
   One bit of advice came right after the Thursday debate, an
encounter that was clearly a disappointment to the Democratic
campaign.
   Dukakis' vice presidential running mate Lloyd Bentsen called and
gave him a pep talk.
   The Texas senator advised the presidential nominee that it was
time to get out and campaign ``flat out'' until Election Day.
   Bentsen has emerged as the Dukakis campaign's greatest asset
with a large majority of voters saying they prefer him to GOP vice
presidential nominee Dan Quayle.
   Jibes at Quayle remain standard parts of Dukakis and Bentsen
campaign speeches.
   The value Dukakis places on Bentsen was seen by the fact that
right after the debate, the Texas senator flew to California for a
joint appearance with the Massachusetts governor.
   The first signs of change in campaign approach were a new pair
of commercials that were very different stylistically from the
often sharp-edged ads he had run before.
   Aides also said every opportunity would be used to get the
candidate before large television audiences. He is ready and eager,
for example, to appear on such programs as ABC's ``Nightline.''
   ``Our best messenger is our candidate,'' said deputy campaign
chairman John Sasso.
   Aides also predicted a far more intense campaign schedule and on
Friday, the day after the debate, Dukakis was on the road from
eight in the morning to well past midnight.
   Aides still maintained they had a clear view of the path to
victory on Nov. 8.
   They talked of the strong grass-roots organization built up over
months and contended the debate had exposed ``several new areas of
vulnerability and weakness'' in Bush.
   And they could point to the crowd of nearly 10,000 that waited
in the rain in Seattle to hear Dukakis on Friday.
   ``We are poised for a strong last three weeks,'' Sasso told a
post-debate briefing.
   ``The road ahead of us is going to be tough,'' conceded the
candidate.
   Advisers admitted that Bush commercials attacking Dukakis for
his state's program granting prison furloughs and for the pollution
in Boston Harbor had put the Democratic nominee on the defensive.
   ``The furlough thing has really hurt,'' said Steve Engelberg, a
political adviser traveling with Dukakis. ``To win we have to get
rid of it and rid of it fast.''
   Dukakis tried to do just that by pointing out that his father
had once been beaten and robbed and that his brother had been
killed by a hit-and-run driver.
   ``I don't need George Bush to tell me about crime,'' he told
audiences.
   The Massachusetts governor also cited the federal furlough
program and specifically the case of a furloughed drug dealer who
raped and murdered a pregnant woman in Arizona.
   Equally damaging was the Boston Harbor commercial run by Bush.
It showed scenes of sludge and dead fish and said Dukakis had
failed to act promptly to clean up the harbor.
   Campaign aides conceded that commercial put Dukakis on the
defensive on the environment, particularly in California, where the
environment was regarded as Dukakis' strongest issue.
   California campaign aides think a Dukakis response commercial
citing Reagan administration cuts in environmental protection
programs has now neutralized the Boston Harbor ad.
   The new national Dukakis commercials are desigmed to deal with a
perception that he is cold, passionless. In them, Dukakis speaks in
a conversational tone and tries to get across his values.
   In one, Dukakis is in shirtsleeves and sitting on a couch.
   ``It's been a few years since Kitty and I had children in
school,'' he says.
   Then after referring to challenges facing young couples today,
he concludes, ``I'd want my president to be in touch with the
things that are important to me and my family.''
</TEXT>
