<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Portugal-SouthAfrica     10-15 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Portugal-South Africa,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Portugal Offers Help In Angola, Mozambique and South-West Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Portugal wants to help rebuild the
war-shattered economies of its former southern African colonies of
Angola and Mozambique, the foreign minister told South African
leaders on Saturday.
   Portugal also is ready to participate in bringing independence
to South-West Africa, Foreign Minister Joao de Deus Pinheiro said.
   He gave Portugal's commitment to ``peace, democracy and
development'' in southern Africa after he and Prime Minister Anibal
Cavaco Silva talked for 90 minutes with South African President
Pieter W. Botha and Foreign Minister Roelof Botha.
   Roelof Botha told reporters after the meeting that they
discussed the progress of U.S.-mediated peace talks among Angola,
Cuba and South Africa aimed at the withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban
soldiers from Angola and independence for South-West Africa, or
Namibia.
   Marxist Angola has been fighting a 13-year-old guerrilla war
with South African- and U.S.-supported rebels.
   South African troops withdrew from Angola into neighboring
South-West Africa in late August as part of a cease-fire agreement
that emerged from the talks.
   Deus Pinheiro also said Portugal was ready to participate in
implementing a U.N. plan for independence elections in South-West
Africa, which South Africa has governed in violation of a U.N.
resolution.
   But he indicated it was too early to say if Portuguese troops
would take part in a U.N. peacekeeping force in South-West Africa.
   Botha said the leaders also discussed recent developments in
Pretoria's relations with Mozambique and the possibilities of
restoring power supplies to South Africa from the mainly
Portuguese-owned Cahora Bassa hydroelectric plant in northern
Mozambique.
   Power lines from the dam to South Africa are regularly sabotaged
by rebels of the Mozambique National Resistence who have been
fighting to topple the leftist Mozambican government since 1977.
   The talks on economic recontruction for southern Africa followed
a call by Deus Pinheiro for a Portuguese-administered $600 million
``mini-Marshall Plan'' for the region.
</TEXT>
