<DOCNO> AP881015-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-88 1412EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w nDennisEckart andI'mbringingyoutheDemocraticresponseto
  10-15 0757</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE> Dennis Eckart, and I'm bringing you the Democratic response
to</2ND_LINE>
<TEXT>
   President Ronald Reagan's weekly address.
   Last month, I had an unusual phone call from Texas Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen. He asked me to play Dan Quayle and help him prepare for
the vice-presidential debate. I eagerly accepted. I thought it
would be fun.
   However, as I began to study up on Sen. Quayle, I realized that
I was studying a controversial man -- a man who did not share the
lives, the needs, and the hopes of many of my constituents in
northeastern Ohio, a man who took every shortcut available, who
never struggled to make ends meet, to make college costs, or to pay
his rent.
   I had to wonder what it was about Dan Quayle that George Bush
liked. I realized there have been a lot of those folks in George
Bush's career -- Robert Bork, Rita Lavelle, James Watt, and Ed
Meese -- and never once did George Bush question their judgment or
their ability to serve. It's no wonder he picked a guy like Dan
Quayle.
   We're now 24 days from a watershed presidential election, a
decision that will take America into the 1990s. And on Thursday,
millions of Americans sat in their living rooms and looked for the
next leader of the free world, because leadership is what the
election is all about -- leaders that believe in the shared values
of the American people and are willing to work with the Congress,
not engage in needless confrontation, the kinds of confrontation
that has resulted in the Democratic Congress overturning a dozen
presidential vetoes on issues like trade, clean water, civil
rights, and job creation.
   Thursday night was the candidacy of the status quo versus the
candidacy of ``we can do better.'' My congressional district in
northeastern Ohio holds to many traditional values -- hard work,
strong moral and religious beliefs, pride in their heritage, and
the accomplishments of their children. But they know that it's been
the Democrats who have worked hard to save their jobs, that it was
George Bush and Dan Quayle who opposed plant-closing and tough
trade laws, but that it was Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen who led the
fight to put America first.
   George Bush has been a silent partner, riddled with corruption,
corruption that has reached into the President's cabinet, to the
Pentagon, from defense contractors to Wall Street. And yet, it was
a Democratic Congress this week that spoke of the shared vision
with the American people and Mike Dukakis in passing a tough ethics
bill that covered ourselves and those who tried to profit from
their connections.
   It was George Bush who called himself an environmentalist, who
wanted to sic the FBI on those who polluted our beaches. But, it
was the Democratic Congress, sharing Mike Dukakis's belief that we
have to end this indiscriminate dumping and pass legislation to end
those who will pollute our beaches with medical waste, and thus,
return the beaches to our children so they can enjoy them.
   It was once again the Democratic Congress that passed sweeping
welfare reform legislation called for by Mike Dukakis in his role
as Massachusetts' Governor. We responded with an appropriate bill
to help take people off of welfare and put them back on productive
payrolls.
   I've watched this campaign closely, not only through my eyes,
but through the eyes of my eight-and-a-half year old son, Eddie,
who's asked me often, ``Dad, what's this all about?'' I've told him
that it's about leadership and shared values, an America that looks
to a new generation of leadership that is both dynamic and just,
leaders who have a sense of compassion, but a commitment to
individual initiative, leaders who can inspire, but are inspired by
our history in a sense that our greatness really is in the future.
   I told Eddie it's a challenge that lies before us. It does not
rest with those who are unwilling to risk something of themselves.
Nor does it rest with those who demand that the struggle be easily
won. It does rest with those who are ready and willing to trade the
comfort and the convenience of the critic for the sweat and the
sacrifice of the committed, and it rests with those of us who have
a hope and a vision for a better America and a better world, and
among all of us who believe that the best of America is yet to
come. Thank you, God bless you, and have a good day.
</TEXT>
