<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Honduras-American     10-15 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras-American,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Killed; Caller Says Leftist Group Responsible</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gunman killed an American who had
lived in Honduras for 26 years, police said Saturday. An anonymous
caller said a left-wing political group was responsible.
   Leo Mills, 63, originally from Woodward, Okla., was shot in the
head Friday with a pistol by a man who was walking down the street
behind him, a police spokesman said.
   A caller told radio stations that a previously unknown group,
the Morazan Front, claimed responsibility for the killing. The
anonymous spokesman said the group was leftist and killed Mills as
a symbol of the social changes that should take place in Honduras.
   Mills had married into a wealthy Honduran family, and he ran
their businesses and large landholdings even after he and his wife
separated.
   He had served an 18-month prison term in the 1981 killing of a
community leader who led squatters in an occupation of some of his
family's land.
   Friends of Mills said his body would be sent to the United
States to be buried in Woodward.
   Police were investigating.
   The Morazan Front apparently was named after Francisco Morazan,
an 1830s political leader who championed Central American unity and
is known as the Abraham Lincoln of Honduras.
</TEXT>
