<DOCNO> AP881015-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-88 1436EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Textbooks     10-15 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Textbooks,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New California Textbooks to Battle `Dumbing Down' Student Fare</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTEREY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a blow against dull and contrived
reading material, California's Board of Education has moved to
reverse the ``dumbing down'' of student textbooks and recapture the
magic of reading.
   The 11-member board on Friday approved a list of 25 children's
books educators said will replace stultifying, formula-dictated
texts with literature and classics of richness and diversity.
   At the same time, board member Armen Sarafian, responding to
criticism about lobbying by textbook publishers, demanded an
investigation by the state attorney general's office into the book
selection process.
   State Superintendent of Public Instruction Bill Honig had said
he thought some board members had become ``too cozy'' with the
publishers, accepting free rides and other things of value.
   California, with 11 percent of the nation's annual $1.5 billion
textbook expenditure, has great clout with the publishers.
   Honig and the board agreed, however, that the new books will go
a long way toward reviving the magic of reading for youngsters, and
exposing them to good writing.
   The exercises in the books stress comprehension rather than
single-word fill-in-the-blank answers that do little to help kids
understand what they have read, Honig said. Textbooks determine an
estimated 90 percent of what teachers teach, state education
officials say.
   Current prescribed texts meet a so-called ``readability
formula'' based on rote, repetition, numbers of syllables in a word
and the word-count in paragraphs _ a dust-dry formula critics say
robs children of the very elements that might motivate them to read.
   As an example, critics pointed to the ``dumbing down'' of
``Little Red Riding Hood'' by one textbook version apparently still
in use. The passage cited has Little Red repeating to exhaustion
the fact that she's got a bunch of apples. Says Red:
   ``I can put red apples in my basket ...
   ``I can put red apples into my basket for Grandma ...
   ``I have red apples ...
   ``I have big red apples ...
   ``I put the apples into my basket.''
   The public school officials were told there has been more
concern with controlling vocabulary than telling the story, with
individual words repeated ``even when they are inappropriate to the
story line.''
   ``Kids have told me that stories about Dick and Jane or Buffy
and Mack are boring,'' said Lisa Izutsu, a third-grade teacher at
Hamlin Street School in Canoga Park. ``Those stories don't spark
their imagination or their creativity. But (children's literature)
really gets them motivated and interested in reading.''
   The official revolt against stupidity in education included
board rejection of all spelling books that had been submitted for
consideration.
   The board declared that spelling should be taught along with
reading and writing, not as an isolated, unconnected exercise.
   Members also decided to require future textbooks to come with a
``consumer warning label'' listing included literary works that had
been abridged, adapted or excerpted. It was the third such decision
in as many years aimed at nudging publishers to provide more
thought-provoking fare for school children.
   In earlier action, the board rejected science texts lacking
detailed explanations of evolution, and math books that neglected
the basics of problem-solving in favor of rote skills.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881015-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-88 1448EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Tito     10-15 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Tito,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Intellectuals Demand Publishing Of Controversial Anti-Tito
Document</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Yugoslavia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of intellectuals who have
denounced Josip Broz Tito are demanding that the state-run media
publish a document that blames the late Yugoslav president for the
country's current crisis.
   The 19-member Committee in Defense of Intellectual Freedoms, in
a statement addressed to the Yugoslav leadership last June 27, said
Tito was to blame for creating an undemocratic, repressive
political system ``which has thwarted the progressive development
of the society.''
   The ruling Communist Party Politburo on Thursday sharply
denounced the statement. It said the document, which calls for a
``critical reapprisal of Tito's role,'' was the strongest attack
yet on the founder of Communist Yugoslavia.
   Now the committee wants its statement to be published by the
state-run press.
   In a statement received by The Associated Press on Saturday, the
committee said officials and the state-run press have branded them
``public enemies,'' even though their document has yet to be
published.
   The committee said it wanted the document to be published so the
public could evaluate its demands. The statement was signed by
prominent Yugoslav university professors, artists and scientists.
   The statement, dated Oct. 11, was addressed to the Yugoslav
Communist leadership.
   Tito, who died in May 1980 after ruling undisputed for 35 years,
is still officially revered in Yugoslavia and public criticism of
his policies can be prosecuted under Yugoslav law.
   ``Tito's role in making crucial political decisions and his
absolute power in shaping Yugoslav policies were so great that the
present-day position of the country, particularly its current deep
social crisis, cannot be understood or explained without a
comprehensive and objective scientific and critical reappraisal of
his historical responsibility,'' the June statement said.
   ``There can be no way out of the present economic, political and
moral crisis affecting Yugoslav society without a thorough critical
evaluation of past Yugoslav policies,'' it added.
   The intellectuals also criticized Tito's non-aligned foreign
policy for ``having isolated our country from its natural,
cultural, historical, economic and political surroundings'' in
Europe.
   The forum denounced Tito's lavish lifestyle, demanding to know
``the real costs of his rule.''
   The document triggered an open clash between national party
chief Stipe Suvar and Serbia's ambitious Communist Party leader
Slobodan Milosevic during the Politburo meeting on Thursday.
   Suvar, from Croatia, accused Serbian leaders of not doing enough
to stop attacks by intellectuals on Tito. Milosevic retorted
angrily that Serbia had been among the first to condemn the
intellectual attacks.
   Although the June document was signed only by 19 prominent
intellectuals, many nonconformist intellectuals consider that
Yugoslavia's current economic crisis, labor and ethnic unrest have
their roots in the Tito years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
