<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Jackson     10-15 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Jackson,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis, at Jackson Party, Jokes About Veep Phone Flap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis early Saturday
attended a birthday tribute to Jesse Jackson, praising his former
rival's work for the Democratic ticket and joking about a
controversy that temporarily strained their relationship.
   ``I didn't know anything about the celebration until today,''
Dukakis said in brief remarks after he arrived at the party just
after midnight. ``Jesse was supposed to call me early this morning
but he never made the call.
   ``I never knew anything about it until I got off the plane from
Sacramento and the press told me about it,'' Dukakis continued.
``Don't you think he'd give me a call first _ before everyone else?'
   The crowd of about 150 people clapped politely at the joke.
   When Dukakis selected Lloyd Bentsen as his running mate last
summer, he called other contenders for the No. 2 spot to inform
them of the choice. But he was unable to reach Jackson, who was
told of the selection by reporters at a Washington airport. Aides
described Jackson as infuriated because he was not notified
personally by Dukakis, and there was friction between the
candidates until they reached an apparent truce at the Democratic
National Convention.
   Dukakis' appearance at the Jackson celebration was one of only a
few joint appearances they have had since the convention.
   Dukakis began his his remarks with a series of jokes, and also
presented Jackson with a VCR and a campaign hat and jacket.
   ``Jesse's given me a lot of advice,'' Dukakis said. ``He's the
guy who told me to tell Bill Clinton to make his speech a little
longer. I told him I was going to ride a tank in Michigan and he
told me `those tanks are dangerous _ wear a helmet.'''
   On a more serious note, Dukakis paid tribute to Jackson's family
and praised him for his voter registration efforts.
   Jackson then took the microphone and challenged his supporters
to rally support for Dukakis and Bentsen.
   ``The governor has set the pace. He established the principles.
articulated the problems,'' Jackson said. ``My friends, Governor
Dukakis can be trusted to keep hope alive, to build the America of
our dreams.''
</TEXT>
