<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-Sinking     10-15 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Sinking,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>At Least 55 Drown After Ferry Sinks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CEBU CITY, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An overloaded ferry boat sank in
heavy seas in the central Philippines, and at least 55 people
drowned, the Coast Guard reported Saturday. It said 77 people were
rescued.
   The Coast Guard said the 35-ton Balangiga was sailing from the
Samar island port of Giporlos to Tacloban on Leyte island when it
sank early Friday after being buffeted by high winds and rough seas.
   Lt. Cesar Cahijas, Coast Guard commander in Tacloban, said four
vessels were dispatched to the area for search and rescue
operations.
   Coast Guard officials said the vessel was authorized to carry 92
passengers and crew. They did not say whether all those aboard the
ship had been accounted for.
   In Manila, Coast Guard officials said they were still awaiting a
complete report from Tacloban.
   Overloading is common on inter-island ferries in the
Philippines. Last December, more than 3,000 people died when the
passenger ship Dona Paz, which was sailing from Tacloban to Manila,
collided with an oil tanker off Mindoro island in the world's worst
peacetime shipping disaster.
   A congressional report cited widespread safety problems in
Philippine commercial shipping, including faulty communications and
lax rescue procedures.
   The Coast Guard, which is responsible for commercial shipping
within this archepeligo country of 7,100 islands, conducted its own
investigation but has not released the findings.
   Last May, at least 53 people died when a motor launch sank in
the same area as Friday's mishap.
</TEXT>
