<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     10-15 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sinhalese Radicals Kill 6 in Sri Lanka</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinhalese anti-government radicals
killed six people, including a policeman whose severed head was
displayed in public, a government statement said Saturday.
   Constable N. Ratnayake, 25, was shot and killed in the southern
town of Matara, 90 miles south of Colombo on Saturday.
   The killers, who are members of the radical Sinhalese People's
Liberation Front, later cut off his head and displayed it, the
statement said.
   The front opposses the Indian-brokered peace accord aimed at
ending the 5-year-old Tamil separatist campaign. The group has been
blamed for over 450 deaths since the accord was signed in July 1987.
   The front has vowed to kill government officials, members of the
security forces, or anyone who supports the accord.
   Also in Matara, a Sri Lankan army soldier was shot and killed by
front gunmen at his home.
   In Kamburupitiya, also in Matara district, three supporters of
the governing United National Party were assassinated on Friday by
front members, the statement said.
   In Ampara, 125 miles east of Colombo, a Sinhalese businessman
was shot and killed.
   The front is opposed to the Tamil aaccord because it says the
peace pact gives too many concessions to the Tamils who make up
only 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people. The Sinhalese
account for about 75 percent of the population.
   The accord has failed after the most powerful of the Tamil
separatist groups, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, rejected
it and said it did not meet the aspirations of the Tamils.
   The Tamils say they are discriminated by the Sinhalese, who
control the government and the military.
</TEXT>
