<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0513,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Attacked With Axes And Knives; Troops Seize Suspected Bomb
Makers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7 grafs for grafs 3-4 pvs, `The Israeli ...' to UPDATE
with Palestinian death, quotes from Israeli victim; PICKS up 5th
graf pvs, `The army ... ' Edits thereafter to trim and conform</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assailants with axes and knives attacked an
Israeli businessman in the West Bank after Israeli forces raided
three nearby villages Saturday and rounded up 20 Palestinians
suspected of making bombs.
   Israeli soldiers, meanwhile, shot and wounded eight Palestinian
protesters in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   A Palestinian shot earlier last week died Saturday of his
wounds, the Israeli-owned Itim news agency reported.
   Itim identified the victim as 19-year-old Ahmed Yaacub Mustafa,
from the village of Qibiya, shot during a demonstration in nearby
Ramallah.
   Mustafa's death raised to 298 the number of Palestinians killed
in the 10-month uprising against Israel's occupation of the West
Bank and Gaza Strip. Six Israelis have died in the uprising.
   The Israeli, 56-year-old David Eliahu, suffered deep gashes in
his head, neck and back when he was attacked in Jenin, 60 miles
north of Jerusalem, the army and Israel army radio said. The
assailants also stole his pistol, the radio said.
   Eliahu had been visiting business acquaintancesin Jenin before
heading off alone, army radio said.
   ``About 30 people attacked me,'' Eliahu later said in a
telephone interview with Israel army radio. ``I tried to run
towards where the army was but they started beating me and I
couldn't get away.''
   Eliahu said he finally managed to reach Israeli military
headquarters.
   The army quoted hospital officials as saying Eliahu suffered
minor injuries and was in stable condition.
   Troops blocked the entrance to Jenin, searched for the
assailants and made several arrests.
   Hours earlier, Israeli police and soldiers raided three villages
near Jenin _ Jalbun, Faqqua and Arabuna _ and uncovered a cache of
explosives, timers and batteries for manufacturing bombs.
   They arrested 20 villagers in possession of the cache. Police
also suspect the group of setting fire to forests in the Mount
Gilboa area in northern Israel, flying Israeli-outlawed Palestinian
flags, blocking roads and taking part in disturbances.
   Israel radio said the group operated inside Israel.
   In other developments Saturday, troops fired on rock-throwing
Palestinian protesters trying to block them from entering the West
Bank village of Qusin, Israel radio said. The army said it was
checking the report.
   Two other Palestinians were shot and wounded in clashes in the
Tulkarm refugee camp and old marketplace of Nablus 50 miles north
of Jerusalem, the radio said.
   In the Gaza Strip, soldiers shot at 100 rock-throwing students
in the souternmost town of Rafah, wounding two teenagers, the army
spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   Three other Palestinians were wounded in clashes with troops in
other parts of the strip.
   Israel officials estimate that 7,000 Arabs have been wounded in
the occupied territories since the Palestinian uprising broke out
Dec. 8. Palestinian sources put the figure at about 18,000.
</TEXT>
