<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ArsonTown     10-15 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arson Town,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>After Tumultuous Week, Town Waits For More Answers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CR1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY MITMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSON, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fireman and a former firefighter have
been arrested but townspeople are certain the book is not closed on
the arson fires that have terrified the community since May.
   ``I don't think anyone believes it's over. Everybody seems to be
looking for another person or two,'' Robert Bruce, owner of the Old
Corner Store, said Saturday.
   ``That's making the assumption that (the two arrested) are even
involved, which is hard for us to accept,'' he said.
   ``There's still a lot of hot tempers,'' said William Perkins,
whose home was burned in May. ``I don't know if the whole mystery
has been solved or not.''
   On Wednesday, Lance Lalumiere, 23, a former member of the
volunteer fire department in this northern New Hampshire community
of 850, was arrested and charged with burning his brother's log
cabin in August.
   One day later, Lawrence Coulter Jr., 19, also a volunteer
firefighter, was charged with setting fire to a vacation home in
nearby Dalton on Oct. 3.
   During a news conference in Concord, authorities said they would
seek indictments against Lalumiere for 15 other fires, and said
they had suspects in five other arsons. They declined to elaborate
   State police Lt. Gary Sloper would not say if authorities
believe the two collaborated, saying only they were investigating
that possibility. Sloper has indicated there may be more arrests.
   On Friday, at a hearing on a prosecution request to revoke
Lalumiere's $50,000 bail, prosecutors filed documents saying
Lalumiere had admitted committing 16 other acts of arson in the
Jefferson area.
   Prosecutors also sought to revoke Coulter's $50,000 cash bail.
During his arraignment Thursday, a state police officer said
Coulter is considered a suspect in the Jefferson fires as well. He
did not elaborate.
   The bail hearings continue Monday and Tuesday. Both men remained
in jail. Neither has entered a plea.
   The fires began in fields and brush and escalated to buildings.
No one was killed or seriously hurt, but more than a dozen people
were left homeless by the 21 fires in Jefferson, two in Lancaster
and one in Dalton.
   Many people stayed up nights to guard their property, with guns
ready.
   Residents described Lalumiere, a dishwasher at a local
restaurant, as a hard worker who left the fire department after
moving out of town for a time. He was under 24-hour surveillance
several weeks before his arrest and had been questioned several
times by police.
   Coulter's arrest was more shocking because of the deep roots his
well-respected family has in the town.
   His father was a firefighter and his mother helped organize a
Sept. 16 fund-raiser that brought in about $10,000 for the fire
department.
   ``There was no reason to ever question his integrity,'' said
Bruce, who employed Coulter part-time the past two years at the Old
Corner Store. ``He was an excellent employee.''
   ``I still think the general feeling in town is there's more
involved in this, if in fact these (two) are involved. I don't
think anyone is ready to accept the fact they are alone,'' he said.
</TEXT>
