<HEAD>Mothers Protest Decision To Open Nuclear Power Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VERACRUZ, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 60 mothers and their children
marched to City Hall on Saturday to protest the government's
decision to open Laguna Verde, Mexico's first nuclear power plant.
   ``I feel helpless, not only for myself, but also for my
children,'' said Rafaela Delfin, a mother of four.
   Jose Luis Alcudia, secretary of energy, mines and industry,
announced Friday that workers would begin loading 92 tons of
uranium into one of Laguna Verde's reactors on Saturday.
   Officials said the loading would take 10-25 days and after
testing the reactor would be ready to generate power within six
months.
   The woman plan to participate in a protest meeting Sunday in
Palmesola, the town nearest the plant at Laguna Verde, located near
the Gulf of Mexico and 30 miles from this port.
