<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0552,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Recalls Past Democratic Comebacks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to update with quote as delivered</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate Lloyd
Bentsen, acknowledging polls showing the Democrats behind, spoke
Saturday of a Democratic comeback this year like those that elected
Harry Truman and John Kennedy.
   ``Our party has a proud tradition of closing from behind and
winning those elections,'' he told about 500 people at an AFL-CIO
regional conference. He said Truman and John Kennedy were also down
in the polls but came back to win.
   ``We're going to do just like Harry Truman. We're going to tell
the truth and the Republicans are going to think it's hell,''
Bentsen told a crowd earlier Saturday at St. Louis' Soulard Market,
in Truman's home state of Missouri.
   ``I can't help but remember Harry Truman out there when the
press had written him off,'' the 67-year-old Texas senator said,
standing on a podium amid the vegetable displays in the open-air
market.
   While polls showed Truman losing to New York Gov. Thomas Dewey,
the Democratic crowds kept getting bigger, he said. ``And I can
still remember that Chicago newspaper saying Dewey had won,'' said
Bentsen, recalling the famous picture of Truman holding up a
newspaper front page.
   In 1960, he said, ``The weekend before (the election), John
Kennedy was eight points behind and went on to win'' because of
``the drive and the commitment and the enthusiasm of the American
people.''
   On a day of campaigning before diverse crowds in Missouri,
Pennsylvania and New York, Bentsen repeated the themes that
Democrats hope will resonate with voters by Election Day, including
trade, jobs, education, Social Security, and a ``squeeze'' on the
middle class.
   Bentsen told the food sellers in St. Louis that American
agriculture exports had declined 40 percent since 1980, and that
600,000 good-paying industrial jobs had been lost.
   ``We're tired of exporting jobs. We want to export products and
keep the jobs here, not in Taiwan or South Korea,'' he said.
   In Wilkes-Barre, at an auditorium filled with mostly elderly
people, he said the Republicans had repeatedly tried to cut Social
Security and Medicare and that George Bush could not be trusted.
   ``I just really can't imagine someone at the age of Social
Security, or close to it, who can vote for that other crowd,'' he
said.
   In his speech at the New York labor rally, Bentsen said the
economic expansion the Republicans were touting was ``a hoax'' for
many Americans.
   ``They've created an economy where the rich get richer, the poor
get poorer and everyone in between gets squeezed,'' he said.
   It was the Democrats who supported, and the Republicans who
opposed raising the minimum wage and giving 60 days notice for
laid-off workers, he said.
   Bentsen was also scheduled in New York to meet with Hispanic
leaders and journalists, and attend a fund-raiser in Brooklyn.
   He was flying to Washington Saturday night but was to return to
the campaign trail on Monday with stops in Texas and California.
   When he talked at his stops about Democratic campaign comebacks,
he also repeated the story of a Democrat who didn't quite overcome
his deficit.
   ``I can't help but think back to what happened to Hubert
Humphrey'' in 1968, he said.
   ``On Oct. 10, Hubert Humphrey was 10 points behind on the polls,
came within seven-tenths of one percent of winning. If he had made
some of those speeches a little shorter, and (made) a few more
stops, he might've made it,'' Bentsen said.
</TEXT>
