<HEAD>Napoleon's Toothbrush Brings in $21,000 At Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A silver- and gold-plated toothbrush
that belonged to Napoleon I sold Saturday for $21,000 at an auction
in Munich, auction officials said.
   The Hermann Historica auction house said the toothbrush,
decorated with the French emperor's coat of arms, was lost at the
battle of Waterloo in 1815. It came from the estate of a British
officer who found it after the battle, a statement from the auction
house said.
   The buyer was not identified.
   The statement said the toothbrush sold for less than the
original asking price of $25,900. It said the utensil had suffered
severe wear through regular use.
   Napoleon died in 1821.
</TEXT>
