<HEAD>Burial Scandal Investigation Continues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A family whose complaint about a
missing burial vault prompted the arrest of a funeral director has
discovered their relative's coffin contains not just the body, but
a load of garbage.
   Relatives of Danny Pitts had his grave opened Oct. 7 after
pallbearers at his funeral said they saw funeral director Bobby
Wilks bury the casket without a vault.
   Pitts' family had planned to rebury him with a vault Friday, but
decided to take a last look inside the coffin.
   Inside, Pitts' body was surrounded by refuse _ a vacuum cleaner
bag full of dirt, empty dog food cans and magazines.
   ``I knew the casket was too heavy,'' said relative Donald Flatt.
   Wilks, charged Friday with six counts of obtaining money under
false pretenses, was in the Robertson County jail Saturday under
$82,500 bond. He also is charged in another county with larceny by
false pretenses, as is his son, Gary.
   Authorities searched the Wilk's Barber Funeral Home and his home
Friday, but would not say what they were looking for.
   Meanwhile, family members of people buried by Wilks continued to
exhume their relatives' bodies this weekend.
   Gary Wilks' wife, Teresa, said her father-in-law was apologetic
when she spoke to him Friday.
   ``All he would say was, `I'm sorry y'all have to be put through
this,'' Teresa Wilks said. ``He's definitely having mental
problems. He's contemplated suicide and he's just not the same
person anymore. He just stares off into space.''
   Exhumations have so far revealed 15 bodies improperly buried by
Wilks' funeral home.
</TEXT>
