<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-15 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scattered Rain, Cool Spell Begins To Abate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain was widely scattered over the central part of the nation
Saturday, and temperatures hit record lows in the Southeast
although the prolonged cold spell across the East was beginning to
relax.
   Showers were widely scattered over the northern Rockies, the
northern Plains, the central high Plains and the lower Great Lakes.
   Showers and a few thunderstorms were scattered from east-central
Missouri to southern Indiana.
   Rainfall totals for the six-hour period up to 2 p.m. EDT were
generally less than a quarter of an inch.
   Record lows reported Saturday were 35 at Athens, Ga.; 43 at
Beaufort, S.C.; 38 at Cape Hatteras, N.C.; 41 at Savannah, Ga., and
35 at Wilmington, N.C. Records were tied at Caribou, Maine, at 25;
at Charleston, S.C., at 40; and Columbia, S.C., at 32.
   However, during the weekend highs were expected to reach the 70s
as far north as Pennsylvania, with 60s over much of New England.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 43
degrees at Caribou, Maine, to 94 at Palm Springs, Calif. Saturday
morning's low for the 48 states was 19 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Sunday, scattered showers and a few thunderstorms were
forecast from the middle Mississippi Valley to the Great Lakes
region and western New England. Scattered showers and thunderstorms
also were forecast from Arizona to southwestern Texas, and across
extreme southern Florida. Showers were forecast from the northern
Pacific Coast to northwestern Montana.
   Highs only in the upper 40s were predicted across northern
Maine; in the 50s across northern Minnesota and much of the rest of
New England; in the 60s from the northern Pacific Coast to the
northern Rockies and from the Dakotas to New York state; in the 80s
across the Florida Peninsula, the southern Plains, the California
valleys and the desert Southwest; and in the 70s elsewhere across
the nation.
</TEXT>
