<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-88 1757EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Children'sHunt     10-15 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Children's Hunt,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Youth Hunt Draws Protest From Animal-Rights Activists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMP BLANDING, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state-sponsored deer hunt for
children as young as 8 drew fire Saturday from animal welfare
groups and educators who claim it's too traumatic to have kids kill
the likes of Bambi.
   A Florida Game and Fresh Water Fish Commission spokesman
defended the hunt in this rural military reservation as a way to
educate youngters about gun safety and hunting etiquette.
   Forty children from 8-to 15-years old, accompanied by adults,
were expected to take part in the weekend shotgun hunt in the wilds
at the sprawling Florida National Guard reservation, southwest of
Jacksonville.
   Three others are scheduled in the next two weeks. The commission
has sponsored similar hunts in the last three years, but without
much protest.
   ``Our worst fears were confirmed _ that little children were in
a sense being indoctrinated to hunt,'' said Wayne Pacelle, director
of the New York-based Fund for Animals, which claims about 200,000
members and is opposed to all hunting. ``We consider this
state-sponsored cruelty.''
   Pacelle, who visited the hunt area Saturday morning, said a
10-year-old and a 13-year-old killed one deer each, the first for
each. The hunt had a 40-deer limit.
   Henry Cabbage, a commission spokesman, said the agency was
providing a public service by helping to teach safety.
   ``These kids applied for these hunts. They're interested in
hunting. Their parents are interested in teaching them,'' Cabbage
said in Tallahassee. ``The Fund for Animals is on record that they
are opposed to hunting. It just gives them a handle to promote
their ultimate objective of taking away the right to hunt.''
   ``Having children kill animals for fun is ridiculous,'' said
Sharon Bailey of North Miami, who heads the Florida chapter of the
Friends of Animals, a national anti-hunting group. ``It twists the
values of our children. I've taken 8-year-olds to see Bambi. Even
that upsets them,'' she said of the animated Disney movie.
   Earlier this week, animal-rights activist Cleveland Amory
confronted Gov. Bob Martinez at a Palm Beach Chamber of Commerce
breakfast and demanded he cancel the state-sanctioned hunt. Amory
is an author who helped found the Fund for Animals.
   Martinez ignored Amory's comments and later said the hunt should
go on. He said it fosters closer relationships between parents and
their children.
   Meanwhile, about 75 protesters turned out and three were
arrested as the Air Force Academy opened its grounds in Colorado
Springs, Colo., to hunters Saturday for the first legal deer hunt
there in 18 years.
   The Rocky Mountain Humane Society led the demonstration on the
academy grounds, and humane society executive director Robin
Doxbury was one of the three arrested on criminal trespass charges.
All three later were released.
   Air Force officials say the 1,500 deer on the reservation are
more than the area can feed, and the hunt is intended to reduce the
population by 80 does. Officials have cited more than 100 traffic
accidents involving deer around the academy in the last year to
argue that the growing deer population poses a danger to the public.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
