<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     10-15 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deborah Miller became a grandmother one
day and a mother the next.
   Miller gave birth to her third child, Michael, at 5 p.m.
Thursday at Reid Memorial Hospital. Eighteen hours earlier, her
oldest daughter, Amanda Beasley, gave birth to her first child,
Alyssa.
   By Friday, they were sharing a room at the hospital.
   ``We knew it would be possible to be close,'' Miller said. ``But
when we were both overdue, we didn't know what was going to
happen.''
   Miller's due date was Oct. 2, her 20-year-old daughter's was
Sept. 27.
   ``Amanda and I have been so close and shared so much. Sometimes,
I have trouble remembering that I'm a mother first,'' said Miller,
37. ``When other mothers call their girlfriends when they need a
shoulder to cry on, I call my daughter.''
   While Beasley was headed for the birthing room, nurses quipped
the two women might share a room.
   ``We joked about this the whole nine months,'' Miller said.
``But we never thought we'd do it.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NORTH PLATTE, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bill and Judy Studham were excited
when they had twins four years ago. They were stunned to learn
another set was on the way this year.
   ``At first it was kind of overwhelming, but we are really
excited about it now,'' Mrs. Studham said, who added that twins run
in both sides of the family.
   Andy and Allan are now getting acquainted with their new
brothers, Adam and Aaron. The new twins were born Oct. 8.
   ``I had wanted twins since I was a little girl,'' Mrs. Studham
said.
   ``At first we were really shocked. We intended to have four
children but had wanted only one this time,'' Mrs. Studham said. As
reality set in, the idea was accepted and the family became
ecstatic, she said.
   None of the twins is identical, said their mother.
   ``I like it that way. I can really see their individuality,''
she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TRAVERSE CITY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To hear Janna VanZile describe it,
Cupid is moonlighting as a postal clerk for the U.S. Navy.
   A letter that she addressed to no particular sailor stationed in
the Persian Gulf found its way to Petty Officer First Class Stephen
A. Woodbury, 25, of Boston, and now they're engaged.
   The pen-pal romance began a year ago, when announcers with
WTCM-AM began asking listeners to write to servicemen in the gulf
as a morale booster.
   VanZile, 23, addressed her letter to any sailor or Marine in the
region. ``I just wrote about myself and the area where I live and
my hobbies,'' she said.
   Woodbury, an intelligence specialist stationed aboard the U.S.S.
LaSalle, received VanZile's letter and wrote back to her shortly
before Christmas. They began corresponding regularly, sometimes
writing two or three letters a day.
   They met in April while Woodbury was on a two-week leave. ``He
called my mom and made arrangements'' to meet, VanZile said. ``I
didn't even know about it.
   The couple hasn't set a wedding date. But VanZile and her
4-year-old daughter, Ashley, are preparing to move to Virginia
Beach, Va., to be near Woodbury, who's stationed in nearby Norfolk.
</TEXT>
