<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0517 10-15 0842</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0517,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Courts Votes In Key States Of California, Texas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LOS ANGELES</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 12 grafs new to UPDATE with Texas appearance; picks up
8th graf pvs, bgng: ``The Massachusetts ...; DELETES last 3 grafs
to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis courted votes Saturday
in the all-important battlegrounds of California and Texas,
defending his crimefighting record and saying his commitment on the
issue ``comes right from my gut.''
   Dukakis ended a four-day stay in California by accepting the
endorsement of four Hispanic law enforcement groups and then flew
to Texas, where he laid a wreath at a Vietnam veterans memorial in
San Antonio and addressed an outdoor rally.
   In addition to defending his crimefighting record and denouncing
that of Republican rival George Bush, Dukakis delivered tailored
messages in each state. He spoke in Los Angeles of his commitment
to the environment and in San Antonio of his promise of national
energy and banking policies to help struggling industries.
   He also spoke warmly of his running mate, Texas Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen.
   ``Lloyd Bentsen and I have formed a partnership _ a partnership
for the future, a partnership that will make America first
economically and militarily,'' Dukakis told the Texas rally.
   ``The two go hand in hand,'' he said. ``You can't have one
without the other and we'll have neither if we elect George Bush
and Dan Quayle to lead our country.''
   Dukakis also pressed his effort to paint Bush as a failed leader
in the war on drugs who also let down the banking industry in his
adopted home state of Texas and offered no vision of the future.
   ``George Bush offers us the politics of complacency,'' Dukakis
told the rowdy San Antonio gathering. ``Lloyd Bentsen and I offer
the challenge of change. George Bush wants us to stick to the
status quo.''
   Dukakis said Republican corruption and misguided decisions on
defense spending had harmed the nation's conventional strength and
were costing jobs at military installations in Texas.
   ``That's why the Republican era of greed and graft and
corruption is going to end at high noon on the day I take the oath
of office as president of the United States,'' Dukakis said.
   Earlier, at the law-enforcement event, the Democrat spoke of
murders in California by inmates on furlough during Ronald Reagan's
governorship. And he said that while Bush has been vice president
there have been thousands of federal prison furloughs and one
incident last year in which an inmate on furlough raped and
murdered a mother of two in Arizona.
   Polls indicate the Republican vice president has been successful
in attacking Dukakis' crime record by citing a Massachusetts
furlough program that granted a pass to a murderer who later raped
a Maryland woman.
   The Massachusetts governor said it was ``cynical and
hypocritical'' for Bush to use the Massachusetts case for political
gain.
   Dukakis said that he and Reagan took responsibility for their
programs but that Bush has refused to take blame for his failures.
   The governor also spoke of the mugging of his father at the age
of 77 and the death of his brother in a hit-and-run car incident.
   ``I didn't learn my lessons about crime from a Clint Eastwood
movie,'' Dukakis said. ``I've been out there with you.''
   He said Bush had failed in leading the Reagan administration's
drug war, and he drew laughter from the audience when mentioning
Bush's proposal to put his running mate, Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle,
in charge of the drug fight.
   ``The only thing, I think, that is cheaper today than it was in
1982 is cocaine,'' Dukakis said, blaming that in part on Bush,
Reagan's point man on drugs.
   He boasted of his state's 14 percent decline in the rate of
major crime, and its rankings as the state with the lowest homicide
rate among industrial states. That progress, he said, resulted from
his personal involvement in a statewide anti-crime council.
   ``This is an issue that is very close to me,'' he said. ``It
comes right out of my gut.''
   Dukakis also tailored part of his message to his California
audience, promising to double the number of federal drug agents and
send the first 100 new agents to southern California.
   ``When southern California and Los Angeles called for help,
where was the administration in Washington? Nowhere to be found,''
Dukakis said. ``It's easy to talk about values. It's a lot tougher
to live up to them. That's really the issue in this campaign, talk
versus action, an understanding of the future.''
   He also spoke Saturday at a birthday tribute to Jesse Jackson,
his former Democratic presidential rival.
   Jackson said, ``The governor has set the pace. He established
the principles. articulated the problems. My friends, Governor
Dukakis can be trustedd to keep hope alive, to build the America of
our dreams.''
   At another rally, Dukakis touched on the environment, another
important issue in California, promising an administration that
supported ``clean air and clean water and clean oceans and clean
government.''
</TEXT>
