<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0537,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Cheered in Wisconsin, Brushes Off Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede APPLETON</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 3 grafs new to UPDATE with rally in Washington; Picks up
3rd graf pvs, bgng: ``He was ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential nominee Dan
Quayle ended a week-long swing through the Midwest and Plains
states Saturday, brushing off protesters at a Wisconsin rally and
proclaiming that the state ``is going for George Bush.''
   At a welcome home rally here staged by Vice President George
Bush's staff, Quayle was presented with a green medical uniform
sporting the words ``Dr. Spin'' and a stethoscope.
   Quayle earlier in the week proclaimed himself ``Dr. Spin'' and
said he would be doing his own ``spinning,'' or interpretation for
the press of campaign developments.
   He was greeted in Wisconsin by cheering supporters in Eau Claire
and Appleton.
   However, he also ran into protests at the University of
Wisconsin at Eau Claire. When he arrived, demonstrators held signs
reading ``What has Quayle done for vets?'' and ``Chickenhawk,'' the
latter a reference to his service at home in the Indiana National
Guard during the Vietnam War.
   ``See you after the election,'' Quayle said as he brushed by
them.
   His speech was briefly disrupted by chants of ``Go home Dan.''
   ``That's the kind of courtesy you get from the Dukakis people,''
Quayle said and the crowd cheered.
   Quayle has criticized the Democratic presidential nominee for
failing, when given the opportunity during Thursday night's debate
with Bush, to say something nice about his opponent. On Friday,
Quayle said Dukakis lacked ``common courtesy.''
   He told the Wisconsin rallies that Bush ``won that debate hands
down.''
   In Appleton, where escape artist Harry Houdini was born, Quayle
joked that Dukakis ``failed miserably'' in ``every escape trick he
tried.''
   Quayle's campaign trips this week took him through Michigan,
Ohio, Indiana, South Dakota, New Mexico, Arkansas, Louisiana and
Wisconsin.
   But the week was most notable for Quayle's statements Wednesday
that he was going to be ``my own handler'' and was taking more
control of his campaign. He said that as someone who has run
successfully for elective office in the past, ``I know what's best
for George Bush.''
   He was reacting to numerous reports that his words and actions
are tightly controlled by Bush campaign officials fearful of what
he might say or do on his own.
</TEXT>
