<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pope-Universities     10-15 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Universities,0176</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope: Catholic Universities Must Adhere To Church Teachings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II told visiting American
bishops Saturday that Roman Catholic colleges and universities in
the United States must be faithful to church doctrine.
   John Paul said the teachings of the church ``can truly be
considered the expression of the infallibility of the church.
   ``Yet this does not prevent the church from recognizing and
promoting a legitimate pluralism in theology.''
   But, he said, that pluralism is ``limited to the unity of the
faith and the authentic teachings of the church.''
   The pope spoke of the ``importance Catholic higher education has
for the future of society and the church in the United States,''
but added, the ``degree of their influence depends entirely on the
preservation of their Catholic identity.''
   John Paul also referred to what he called the ``damaging
repercussions'' of the ``right to dissent'' on moral conduct.
   ``It is not the conscience that establishes liberally what is
right and what is wrong,'' he said.
</TEXT>
