<DOCNO> AP881015-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-88 1835EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ElephantAbuse     10-15 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Elephant Abuse,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Animal Rights Group Claims Responsibility in Attacking Trainer
Property</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A radical animal rights group claimed
responsibility for defacing the homes and cars of three trainers
involved in the disciplinary beating of a zoo elephant.
   Members of the Animal Liberation Front poured red paint on the
trainers' cars, let air out of their tires and splashed their homes
with abrasive paint-stripping chemicals either early Friday or late
Thursday night, said Nancy Burnet, director of the Coalition to
Protect Animals in Entertainment.
   The dispute that has been broiling since February over the
chaining and beating of the animal has included investigations by
the local and national Humane Society, the city attorney's office
and the American Association of Zoological Parks and Aquariums.
   Burnet, who said she does not belong to the Animal Liberation
Front but supports its action, told The Associated Press she
received a call from a group member Friday claiming responsibility
for the vandalism.
   The trainers were all employees of the San Diego Zoological
Society, said San Diego Zoo spokeswoman Martha Baker. No one was
injured in the episode, she said.
   ``We are outraged that the victims and their families have been
terrorized in such a manner,'' said Doug Myers, executive director
of the zoological society, which operates the zoo and affiliated
Wild Animal Park. ``Personally attacking our employees is purely
reprehensible.''
   In a statement released through Burnet, the group said its acts
were in response to the trainers' handling of Dunda, an 18-year-old
African elephant at the Wild Animal Park near Escondido in northern
San Diego County.
   When Dunda was transferred from the zoo to the Wild Animal Park
in February, the trainers reported that she became unruly and at
one point acted like she was trying to kill them.
   To prevent the elephant from getting out of control, the
trainers said they had to chain the animal and beat her repeatedly
with wooden sticks.
   The Zoological Society defended the trainers' actions, saying
they took the necessary steps to regain control of Dunda. Others
have criticized the form of discipline, including several park
employees who witnessed it.
   The national Humane Society called the beating an isolated case
of animal abuse, but left any changes in the handling of elephants
to the Zoological Society's discretion. The local Humane Society
and the city attorney's office, cleared the zoo of abuse
allegations.
   In response to the situation, the American Association of
Zoological Parks and Aquariums created a task force to set
nationwide elephant training standards considered later by its
board of directors. Last month, the group ruled the San Diego
trainers did not violate ethical standards.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
