<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Iacocca     10-15 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Iacocca,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler Chairman To Chinese: Improve Quality</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee A. Iacocca on
Saturday told his Chinese partners they must improve quality in
order to compete in the international auto market.
   ``Mostly we talked straight about quality,'' Iacocca said of his
discussions with Beijing Jeep Corp., which is 31 percent owned by
Chrysler.
   ``You must get quality up. Quality comes up, productivity comes
up, costs go down and the world will recognize you as an exporter.
If you don't do that, you can't play,'' Iacocca said.
   He told a news conference that another key problem was getting
enough foreign exchange to increase volume to the level where
world-class quality suppliers will invest in the company.
   ``If there was one single thing we tried to emphasize this week
it was we must prime the pump somewhat to get some volume going,''
he said.
   Beijing Jeep, a joint venture begun in 1983 between American
Motors Corp. and the Beijing Automobile Works, shut down its
assembly lines and almost collapsed in 1986 because it lacked
foreign currency to buy needed parts.
   The Chinese government bailed out the enterprise, which this
year will produce about 4,000 Jeep Cherokees and 25,500 light-duty
four-wheel-drive jeeps called the BJ212.
   Chrysler took over AMC's share of the business when it bought
the company last year.
   Iacocca said production of the Cherokee must be increased to
10,000 and then 15,000 vehicles in the coming years to make the
operation more viable.
   He also emphasized quality, a persistent problem in China, in a
speech before 300 Chinese businessmen and officials in the Great
Hall of the People.
   ``The price of entry in the international automobile market is
quality,'' he said. ``If you don't have the best product in its
class, don't try to compete.''
   He urged Chinese automakers to develop their own market before
exporting. China last year produced 472,000 vehicles, almost all
trucks and buses, and has outlined ambitious plans for rapid
expansion.
   Its passenger car industry, just getting off the ground, so far
has been based entirely on joint ventures, with Chrysler producing
in Beijing, Volkswagen in Shanghai and Peugeot in Canton.
   Iacocca, who celebrated his 64th birthday Saturday, arrived
Monday for his first trip to China.

</TEXT>
