<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-DrugRecall     10-15 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Drug Recall,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heath Ministry Orders Drug Recalled After Four Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Health Ministry ordered the removal of a plasma
substitute from hospitals Saturday following the deaths of four
people who had been treated with it, the Italian news agency ANSA
reported.
   The ministry emphasized the removal was ``preventative.''
   It said in a communique that four men had died at the Lancisi
Hospital in the northern city of Ancona after receiving the
Italian-made plasma substitute Hespan prior to heart operations.
   The patients, aged from 48 to 68, died over a one-month period,
the medical director of Ancona hospitals and the president of the
national medical workers' organization said Saturday at a news
conference, according to ANSA.
   The patients, who received the plasma substitute because of
heart circulation problems, suffered a sudden drop in blood
pressure before their deaths, the officials said.
   The assistant prosecutor of Ancona, Marcello Monteleone, ordered
the patients' records seized, ANSA said. Monteleone said it was not
yet clear what caused the four deaths and said they could have
resulted from technical problems or the action of other drugs.
