<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChristianCenterDeath 1stLd-Writethru a0565 10-15 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Christian Center Death, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0565,0650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two More Charged With Murder in Girl's Death</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: DELETES reference to Olympics in lede; DELETES reference to
spiritual leader in 3rd graf, `The girl's...';
^By WILLIAM C. CRUM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Pres Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANDY, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two more staff members were charged with
murder Saturday in the beating death of the 8-year-old daughter of
the leader of a Los Angeles group organized to help disadvantaged
inner-city children.
   Fifty-three other children, possibly victims of abuse, were put
in state custody after the death Friday of Dayna Lorea Broussard.
   The girl's father, Eldridge Broussard Jr., is the leader of the
Watts Christian Center and founder of the Ecclesia Athletic
Association, intended to train and discipline youngsters in the
Watts area of Los Angeles.
   The dead child was beaten on her head, chest and extremities and
died of ``multiple blunt-force injuries,'' said state Medical
Examiner Larry V. Lewman.
   The three charged with murder were connected to Broussard's
group, Clackamas County sheriff's spokeswoman Judy Gage said
Saturday.
   Willie K. Chambers, 35, of San Diego, was charged Friday and
held without bail in the county jail. Charged Saturday were
Constance Zipporah Jackson, 37, and Frederick Paul Doolittle, 28,
both of Los Angeles. They were jailed pending arraignment Monday.
Chambers is the father of a student at the center.
   The 53 children, aged 3 months to 16 years and all reportedly
from Los Angeles, were taken by state authorities from a farm house
eight miles east of Sandy and placed in juvenile shelters and
foster homes.
   Capt. Pat Detloff of the sheriff's department said several of
the children had old scars that indicated they may have been
physically abused.
   ``All the children were given a preliminary medical
assessment,'' Bart Wilson, branch manager for the state Childrens
Services Division, said Saturday. ``All I know is that nobody has
any serious injuries or anything, but that's a pretty speculative
statement.''
   He said the children would be examined and interviewed over the
weekend.
   Gage said Jackson and Doolittle were with the children in the
sparsely furnished house at the time authorities arrived.
Investigators said the children were sleeping on pillows on the
floor.
   Officials said Chambers and three other adults brought the dead
child to a fire station in a rural area 25 miles east of Portland
early Friday.
   The three adults who accompanied Chambers, and who also were
connected with Broussard's group, were charged with hindering
prosecution and jailed in lieu of $100,000 bail each.
   Alvin Broussard, reached by telephone at the Watts center
Saturday, said his brother left Los Angeles by car late Friday en
route to Oregon.
   Eldridge Broussard, 35, was a star basketball player at Pacific
University in Forest Grove, Ore., in the 1970s. He founded the
controversial athletic association in 1975. The organization
brought an estimated 70 to 100 men, women and children from Los
Angeles to the Sandy area in April 1987. Broussard said they were
there to grow vegetables and train, especially for Olympic-style
games he hoped to one day establish in Africa.
   The group left the area, returning to Los Angeles in June 1987
after neighbors opposed Ecclesia's applications for zoning permits
to allow 55 children and 45 adults to live in tents and use
portable toilets and showers.
   The children reportedly had been in the area since late summer.
   Carolyn Van Brunt, a spokeswoman for Broussard, said Friday
night from Los Angeles that the group sometimes uses ``physical
correcton'' as a form of discipline, but denied the punishment was
cruel.
   ``These kids are from Watts and they have to deal with gangs and
drugs and people with no discipline,'' she said.
   ``The staff members, the volunteers, are certainly dismayed at
this very unfortunate occurrence,'' she added. ``But no one's
holding any grudge against anyone. Somebody made a mistake.''
</TEXT>
