<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-88 2010EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ShigellosisOutbreak     10-15 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shigellosis Outbreak,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Number Of Flights Possibly Affected Rises To 60</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Passengers from about 60 Northwest Airlines
flights over the last month were being sought Saturday as health
officials tried to identify the source of an illness that may have
stricken hundreds of people.
   Laboratory tests have confirmed cases of the bacterial illness
shigellosis in passengers from five Northwest flights, and
officials have received calls from passengers on about 60 flights
between Sept. 15 and Oct. 10 who say they suffered symptoms that
may be those of shigellosis, said state Health Department spokesman
Buddy Ferguson.
   The outbreak came to light after 21 players and staff members of
the Minnesota Vikings football team became acutely ill two to five
days after their game in Miami Oct. 2. State epidemiologist Michael
Osterholm said the Vikings, some of their family members and two
Miami locker room workers became ill after eating catered
sandwiches after the game and in the following days.
   Shigellosis is an intestinal infection that causes intense
diarrhea and other symptoms that can last for five to seven days.
The illness spreads easily from person to person.
   All the illnesses confirmed so far have been traced to food
prepared in Marriott Corp.'s airline kitchen at the Minneapolis-St.
Paul International Airport. The facility prepares 100,000 meals a
week for Northwest.
   ``We're into a phase where we're trying to deal with some of the
reports we've gotten in from the public about becoming ill, and
trying to determine whether those are probable cases of
shigellosis,'' Ferguson said.
</TEXT>
