<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-88 2017EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-US-Finance     10-15 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-US-Finance,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Say U.S. Back Dues Threaten Peacekeeping Missions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to restore cycle designator</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N. official said Saturday that if the
United States withholds some of the dues President Reagan promised
to pay, it would threaten an independence plan for South-West
Africa and other peacekeeping missions.
   The United States paid $85.6 million Friday, reducing the
American arrears to the regular budget to $366.3 million.
   U.N. officials refused to confirm or deny a report published
Saturday by The New York Times that said the United States would
withhold $59 million of $188 million Reagan pledged to pay by the
end of the year.
   The report said the funds would be frozen until the General
Assembly's main financial committee, the Fifth Committee, adopts an
austerity budget recommended last month by a subcommittee.
   U.N. financial spokesman Fred Eckhard said Saturday that if the
U.S. withheld dues it would be ``a disappointment,'' and impinge on
some U.N. peacekeeping missions.
   Caroline Dulin, a spokeswoman for the U.S. Mission to the United
Nations, said the administration had no reaction to the reports.
   On Sept. 13, Reagan announced he would release $188 million in
unpaid American dues, saying he was satisfied with the U.N.'s
progress on budgetary and other reforms and approved the payment.
   But ever since Reagan took office eight years ago his
administration has harshly criticized the United Nations for what
it calls anti-Western bias, bureaucracy and waste, and has withheld
$700 million in dues to the regular budget, peacekeeping forces and
U.N. agencies.
   Eckhard pointed out that South Africa, Cuba and Angola have
approved Nov. 1 as the date on which the United Nations can begin
implementing an independence plan for South-West Africa, also known
as Namibia.
   The independence plan is estimated to cost $600 million to $700
million for one year, and Eckhard said the United Nations would
need $100 million to $200 million up front to launch the plan _
funds the world body doesn't have.
   The United Nations has no reserve funds, and operates by
spending dues it collects almost as soon as it receives them.
   Eckhard said the United Nations has so far only collected a
fraction of the $35.7 million it assessed members for the first
quarter of a peacekeeping mission in the Persian Gulf.
   Another peacekeeping operation that may require U.N. funds is a
proposal to send 2,000 observers to the Western Sahara to monitor a
referendum on independence for the region.
</TEXT>
