<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Northwestern Gift,0157</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Patient Repays Doctors For Gift Of Life With $17 Million Donation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reuben Feinberg thanked the doctors who saved his
life through heart surgery by giving $17 million to the
Northwestern University Medical School.
   Feinberg, whose father, Joseph, died of heart disease, is
donating the money to establish a cardiovascular research center.
   The donation, from the Joseph and Bessie Feinberg Foundation in
Chicago, is the third largest single gift ever made to the school,
said University President Arnold R. Weber.
   Feinberg said he first approached medical school doctors about
making a major donation while recovering from heart surgery last
year at Northwestern University Memorial Hospital.
   ``I never had thought about giving money to a hospital before
then,'' said Feinberg, 70, who is president and director of the
Jefferson State Bank in Chicago.
   ``I was thinking more about a building or something. But bricks
don't accomplish much. People can.''
</TEXT>
