<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0562 10-15 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0562,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says Lead Won't Make Him Complacent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 8th graf pvs, bgng: ``Bush was ...'' to
UPDATE with later Bush appearance.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MODESTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, vowing to ``go the extra
mile to fight hard'' in the closing weeks of the presidential race,
campaigned Saturday with Hollywood stars and time-tested attacks on
Democratic rival Michael Dukakis.
   Fighting for an advantage in California, where the contest is
too close to call, Bush rode down state highway 99 on a bus tour
through the San Joaquin Valley, trying to energize Republicans and
win over Democrats who had put their allegiance aside to vote for
President Reagan.
   ``California could well be the single key to this election,''
Bush told hundreds of people gathered for a Main Street rally in
Ripon, population 6,700.
   As his caravan rolled past highway crowds, Bush's wife Barbara
prompted him to stick his head out the right window and wave. Son
Jeb Bush, spotting a larger crowd on the left, called out, ``Dad,
you ought to get on the other side.'' He promptly switched.
   ``Here we go ... entering the home stretch of this national
presidential election,'' Bush declared earlier at a noisy kickoff
rally in an airport hangar in Modesto. He pledged to ``redouble our
efforts for the next 24 days'' and ``go the extra mile to fight
hard.''
   ``We're going to take the high road and leave the pessimism and
the tearing down of America to somebody else.''
   Stressing differences with Dukakis, Bush told crowds he supports
voluntary prayer in public schools, and recitation of the Pledge of
Allegiance. ``I don't believe we need more federal gun control. I
don't want somebody from Harvard telling me what I can do and what
I can't do,'' Bush said.
   Bush was accompanied by actors Telly Savalas and Chuck Norris
and by Beach Boys singers Mike Love and Bruce Johnston.
   The vice president closed his daylong trip with a tailgate party
at Fresno State University, where its Bulldogs met Utah State in a
football game. He told the picnicing crowd, ``I'm absolutely
confident that if I can win the state of California I will be the
next president of the United States.''
   From Fresno, Bush was flying to Denver where he planned to spend
two nights.
   At the start of the day, Bush told reporters on Air Force Two
that he was going to stick with familiar themes and not do anything
new that might jeopardize the lead that polls indicate he has.
   ``I'm not going to mess up,'' Bush said. ``Might make a mistake
about Pearl Harbor but I'm not going to mess up.'' In a
well-publicized blooper, he mistakenly said last month that the
anniversary of the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor was Sept. 7
instead of Dec. 7.
   ``My sense is that we seem to be moving in the right direction
but keep on going,'' Bush said. ``I don't think you'll see any
change in game plan or anything of that nature.''
   He said his campaign theme Saturday was ``no different than any
other day.''
   Insisting ``there is not one scintilla of overconfidence in my
makeup,'' Bush said, ``we're going to drive right down to the
wire.''
   He said Dukakis ``is not going to out-hustle me, outwork me.''
   Refusing to speculate about victory, Bush said, ``I can't look
back and I can't look forward beyond Nov. 8, either.''
   He said he was locked into a ``unifocus.''
   ``You're talking to a guy that maybe even some here thought was
out of the race from time to time,'' he said, asking why he should
``now turn around and think everything is roses.''
   Asked if he had a plan to help the battered savings and loan
industry, Bush said ``nobody knows'' how much it will cost
taxpayers for a bailout.
   ``It would be a good place to start and reassure the depositors
that they are in no jeopardy at all,'' Bush said. Told that Senate
Republican Leader Bob Dole had estimated it might cost the
government as much as $50 billion, Bush said, ``I have no plan for
a $50 billion bailout.''
   Some analysts have suggested a merger of the well-financed
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. with the Federal Savings and Loan
Insurance Corp., but Bush said, ``I don't believe we need to do
that right now. We need to keep working out of the difficulties and
be sure that the funds are available for these takeovers and to
protect the depositors, above all.''
</TEXT>
