<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AmnestyConcert     10-15 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amnesty Concert,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Final Concert Of 6-Week Tour Held At Soccer Stadium</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Amnesty International human
rights concert tour, which began six weeks ago in London, concluded
Saturday in this capital before 70,000 fans.
   Rock stars Bruce Springsteen, Sting, Tracy Chapman, Youssou
N'Dour and Peter Gabriel joined Argentine singers Charly Garcia and
Leon Gieco in the concert at River Plate soccer stadium with ``Get
Up, Stand Up,'' the reggae song by the late Jamaican singer Bob
Marley.
   In all, more than 1 million people turned out in 19 cities on
five continents to hear the performers explain the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights, endorse Amnesty International and, of
course, sing.
   ``We look forward to reaching billions of people'' with the Dec.
10 worldwide telecast of Saturday's concert, said John Healey,
executive director of Amnesty International USA.
   ``I'm here for both the music and the message,'' said Vanesa
Gonzalez, 18, of Buenos Aires. ``I'd heard of the declaration
before and I think this is a good way to let others know about it.''
   The declaration, adopted by the U.N. General Assembly in 1948,
says human beings have political, social and economic rights that
no government should curtail and criticizes discrimination based on
race, sex and creed.
   Many in the crowd cheered as the Mothers of the Plaza de Mayo,
white shawls covering their heads, marched into the stadium in a
single column.
   The group, which holds weekly marches in a plaza facing
Argentina's Government House, formed to seek the whereabouts of
people who vanished without a trace during military government
repression of suspected leftists in the 1970s.
</TEXT>
