<1ST_LINE>r a AM-High-DefinitionTV 1stLd-Writethru a0586 10-15 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-High-Definition TV, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0586,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC Proposes Standards For Advanced Television System</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spokeswoman to spokesman in 4th graf bgng, ``It
will...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC on Saturday unveiled its proposal for a new
high-quality television system which the network said could bring
enhanced sound and picture quality into American homes within three
years.
   NBC presented its proposal for production standards for
high-definition television to the Society of Motion Pictures and
Television Engineers at the group's convention Saturday in New York.
   The standards have the backing of a number of U.S. television
makers and ABC-TV, said NBC.
   ``It will not make obsolete the existing 160 million TV sets
Americans now own,'' said NBC spokesman Joe Rutledge.
   High-definition TV produces clearer, brighter images on a wider
TV screen with high-quality sounds. Demand for high-definition
television is expected to grow substantially in the next few years
as picture tubes become larger and screens wider. The advancement
is also seen as a technology to put new life in the American
electronics industry, Rutledge said.
   The Federal Communications Commission last month set preliminary
guidelines to allow research to proceed toward establishing an
American high-definition system. Under the FCC guidelines, a U.S.
system must be able to be received on existing TV sets so current
equipment would not become obsolete. But to receive improved
picture quality, viewers would have to buy a new TV set.
   The FCC's action, Rutledge said, removed a lot of the
``regulatory hoops'' and is expected to facilitate approval of
NBC's proposed standards.
   ``Although technological developments and congressional and
regulatory approval are yet to be completed, the television
industry is hopeful that it can be achieved within three years,''
Rutledge said.
   About 20 advanced-TV systems are under development and competing
to be designated as the U.S. standard.
   The Society of Motion Pictures and Television Engineers sets
national standards in television production and motion pictures.
   The standards announced by NBC have been endorsed by the ABC-TV
network as well as several television makers, including Zenith and
North American Philips, NBC said.
   Rutledge said NBC had invested some $50 million in the
technology.
</TEXT>
