<HEAD>Millionaire Winners Celebrate With Party, Fireworks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALTOONA, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple who won $46 million in
Pennsylvania's 1987 Super 7 Lottery celebrated their good fortune
Saturday night with a dinner party for about 125 people and
fireworks for the whole town.
   Donald R. Woomer Sr. and Linda K. Despot hit the jackpot a year
ago Friday.
   ``We enjoy doing things like this, where you can help in a small
way,'' Ms. Despot, 38, said.
   ``I figure winning that much money, we could do at least that
much for the community, give them a nice fireworks display,''
Woomer, 56, agreed.
   Woomer and Ms. Despot, who live in nearby Hollidaysburg, invited
relatives, neighbors and lottery officials to Saturday night's
dinner at a banquet hall. The couple arrived in a black limousine.
   The dinner guests selected from a buffet of filet mignon,
swordfish, chicken and ham, then enjoyed a half-hour of fireworks
set off at an amusement park.
   Rich Dennis, a disc jockey from a local radio station, played
music from the 1950s and 1960s. It was Dennis who read the winning
numbers for the lottery on Oct. 14, 1987.
   Woomer, a self-employed plasterer prior to Oct. 14, 1987, and
Ms. Despot, a former bookkeeper, began planning the bash last
summer.
   Neither knew how much the evening would end up costing. Neither
one cared.
   ``There's no budget,'' Ms. Despot said. ``If this one goes off
real well, it will be an annual thing.''
