<HEAD>Theft of Telephone Cables Leave 30,000 Without Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some 30,000 homeowners and
businesses in the Buenos Aires area were without phone service
Saturday after thieves stole thousands of yards of telephone cable
from underground channels.
   But phone company officials predicted the thieves would be
disappointed.
   The state-operated National Telecommunications Co. (ENTEL) said
the thieves stole the cable early Saturday in half a dozen suburban
areas apparently believing it was made of copper that could be
melted and sold.
   An ENTEL official said the thieves ``are in for a disagreeable
surprise'' because most of stolen cable was made of glass-based
optical fiber, not copper.
   He said replacement of the cables will take at least a week.
