<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Yellow Fever,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Health Ministry Warns Of Yellow Fever Outbreak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Health Ministry, warning of a
possible outbreak of yellow fever and dengue fever, called Saturday
for a clean-up of stagnant water in this capital city.
   Health Minister Francisco Sanchez Cardenas issued a bulletin
warning that ``the consequences could be catastrophic'' if Panama
City residents do not clean up stagnant water sites that abound in
this city of nearly 1 million.
   No cases of dengue or yellow fever have been reported in Panama
City. However, health officials last week found the mosquito that
transmits the diseases in two Panama City neighborhoods.
   Yellow fever impeded the first attempts to build the Panama
Canal in the last century. But the aedes aegypti mosquito that
spreads the contagious disease was eradicated from the country two
decades ago, Sanchez Cardenas said.
   People can be vaccinated against yellow fever, but not dengue
fever, the health minister said.
</TEXT>
