<HEAD>Grass Fire Hits Wildlife Preserve</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with fire subdued and acreage burned.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HORICON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grass fire swept through the Horicon
Marsh wildlife preserve Saturday, blocking travel on highways with
billowing clouds of smoke that could be seen for 25 miles.
   The Dodge County sheriff's office said winds that spread the
flames died down by 10 p.m., about seven hours after the fire
started. The fire burned 2,500 to 3,000 acres.
   The burn area was estimated about two miles wide, with flames
crawling north about the same distance. Wind spread flames through
tall weeds and underbrush common to the marsh.
   The marsh is an important stopping point for geese and other
migratory waterfowl. Parts of it are in the Horicon National
Wildlife Refuge while an adjoining southern portion is supervised
by the state Department of Natural Resources.
