<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SKorea-SovietUnion     10-15 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SKorea-Soviet Union,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seoul, Moscow Agree To Exchange Trade Offices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea and the Soviet Union,
which have no diplomatic relations, signed an agreement Saturday to
exchange trade offices.
   The accord, in the form of a memorandum, was signed by Vladimir
Golanov, vice president of the Soviet Union's Chamber of Economy
and Industry, and Lee Sun-kee, president of the state-run Korea
Trade Promotion Corp.
   South Korean officials said a formal agreement will be signed in
December when Lee visits Moscow.
   The trade offices, to be opened in Moscow and Seoul, will
encourage trade and invest in each other's country, the officials
said.
   One official, requesting anonymity, said the two sides came to
an understanding that in the absence of diplomatic relations, the
trade offices will be empowered to handle consular affairs.
   Since his arrival Tuesday, Golanov has held extensive talks with
South Korean government and business leaders to promote economic
cooperation between the two countries.
   Business officials quoted Golanov as saying that the Soviet
Union-South Korean interests include the development of Siberia and
joint ventures in automobiles, steelmaking, electronics and
construction.
   South Korea is pushing to promote trade and economic cooperation
with the Soviet Union and East European countries. It has recently
exchanged trade offices with Hungary and Yugoslavia.
   South Korea and China, which have no formal ties, are also
negotiating to set up trade offices in each other's capital,
according to industry sources.
</TEXT>
