<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Frank and Barry obits; AMs separate on Qian moved as
a0641, on Frank as a0873, on Barry as a0872 and on sports wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Melvin Frank</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Melvin Frank, a writer-director-producer who
helped create ``White Christmas,'' ``Mr. Blandings Builds His Dream
House,'' and ``A Touch of Class,'' died Thursday of complications
from heart surgery. He was 75.
   Frank and his partner of 38 years, Norman Panama, teamed for
eight films, including comedies that included ``The Court Jester''
and ``My Favorite Blonde'' and the Broadway musical ``Li'l Abner,''
which they later filmed.
   Born in Chicago, Frank met Panama in 1933, and two years later
they collaborated on comedy material for Milton Berle and Bob Hope.
They would go on to earn three Oscar nominations together. Frank
got his fourth nomination for ``A Touch Of Class'' for his writing
with Jack Rose.
   Among the films Frank produced were ``Prisoner of Second
Avenue'' and ``Lost and Found.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Qian Changzhao</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Qian Changzhao, a former official in the
Nationalist government and a ranking member of the mainland version
of the Kuomintang party, died Friday at the age of 89.
   Qian was vice chairman of the Revolutionary Committee of the
Chinese Kuomintang, one of eight small non-communist parties
permitted to exist by the ruling Communist Party.
   He was also vice chairman of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference, a national advisory body.
   He stayed in China after the Nationalists fled to Taiwan in 1949
and in 1954 was elected as deputy from Shandong province to the
National People's Congress.
   Before 1949 he served as secretary of Chiang Kai-shek's Foreign
Ministry, executive vice minister of education and director of the
National Resources Commission.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Norman Barry</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Norman Barry, a former judge and state legislator
who played college football at Notre Dame with the legendary George
Gipp before becoming a professional player and coach, died
Wednesday at age 88.
   Barry was coach of the National Football League's Chicago
Cardinals and led them to the league championship in 1925. He won
coach of the year honors.
   Barry was elected to the state Senate in 1942 and served 10
years before becoming a Cook County circuit judge. Barry retired
from the bench in 1978 and returned to private practice.
   Last month he attended the dedication of the Norman Barry
Courtroom at the Notre Dame law school.
   He was the right halfback for Notre Dame from 1919-1921, and
teamed with the legendary George Gipp during two of those years.
   After graduating, Barry played for the Chicago Cardinals and the
Green Bay Packers before being named coach of the Cardinals.
   The Chicago Cardinals became the St. Louis Cardinals in 1960.
   Earlier this year, he received the Distinguished American Award
from the National Football Foundation.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Bob Angers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAFAYETTE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bob Angers, business editor for The Daily
Advertiser in Lafayette, died Thursday in a Houston hospital of
leukemia. He was 68.
   During a 50-year career, Angers worked at a number of Louisiana
newspapers, including The Franklin Banner-Tribune and The Daily
Iberian.
   The retired Army major founded the Jeanerette Weekly and the
Southwest Louisiana Capitalist as well as the Acadiana Profile
magazine, now published by his son, Trent Angers.
   Angers was a former president of the state Jaycees and of the
Louisiana Press Association.
</TEXT>
