<HEAD>Historic House Survived Union Cannonball, But Not Vagrants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALATKA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A historic house that withstood a Union
cannonball was destroyed in a fire believed to have been set by
vagrants, officials said.
   The two-story frame house, one of nine pre-Civil War homes
remaining in this north Florida town, was built between 1857 and
1860 by Henry A. Gray, a steamboat captain and barge operator. It
was damaged by the cannonball during the Civil War in 1864.
   Capt. John Holley, Palatka's fire marshal, said electric and gas
service to the vacant house had been cut off when the fire began
Thursday.
   ``The Police Department had been running out some vagrants who
had been staying there,'' Holley said. ``They might have tried to
build a fire in the fireplace there.''
</TEXT>
