<2ND_LINE>AM-Libyans Fined,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Fines Four $100,000 Each in Libyan Case, Orders Three
Deported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge fined three Libyans
$100,000 each Friday and ordered them to leave the country after
they pleaded guilty to conspiring to violate the U.S. economic
embargo on Libya.
   A Moroccan, Manhal B. Mohamed, was fined $100,000 but still
sought to avoid deportation in the case which began in July with
the arrest of the four Arabs. The judge has yet rule on his
possible deportation.
   They initially were charged with conspiring to use Libyan funds
intended for students to finance anti-American political activities.
   The three Libyans were Mahdi M. Abousetta, Milad Shibani and
Ramadan T. Balgasem, all former officials of the Peoples Committee
for Libyan Students, based in McLean, Va.
   Libya established the organization to disburse money to Libyan
students in this country. But prosecutors charged that it also was
a front for the illegal diversion of funds, barred by trade
sanctions imposed by the Reagan administration.
   The pleas came before U.S. District Judge Albert V. Byran,
sitting in Alexandria, Va. He fined the four and ordered the
Libyans out of the country by Nov. 10.
   Three others were arrested at the same time as those who were
fined on Friday. One pleaded guilty last week. A second is set to
appear in court on Monday. And the third has fled the country,
prosecutors said.
</TEXT>
