<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-88 0011EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FoodGiveaways     10-15 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Food Giveaways,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Legislation Boosts Food Giveaway Funds By $120 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department is going to buy an
additional $120 million worth of food for distribution to needy
people next year under recently enacted anti-hunger legislation.
   Assistant Secretary John W. Bode said Friday the food will be
purchased by USDA and sent to food banks and other outlets
beginning in January and continuing through September 1989.
   Bode said the quantities of food purchased will depend on
``market conditions'' at the time, but that plans now call for the
commodities to include peanut butter, canned pork, beans, egg mix
and raisins.
   The program is the Temporary Emergency Food Assistance Program,
or TEFAP, which began in December 1981 when President Reagan
authorized distribution of government-owned food to help reduce the
surplus stockpile of certain commodities, notably cheese, but also
including a variety of other products.
   As TEFAP developed, the surpluses dwindled so that the
department has had to trim the list of items for donation _ after
giving away more than 5 billion pounds of food worth more than $5
billion.
   That is when Congress stepped in with the recent Hunger
Prevention Act of 1988, which authorizes about $1.65 billion over
three years to bolster the government's emergency food programs,
including more funds for food stamps, school breakfasts, child-care
and summer food programs.
   The law also extended TEFAP for two years and provided money for
the additional purchases.
   Bode said that in addition to the $120 million of additional
purchases, the USDA's Commodity Credit Corp. still has $121.9
million worth of food available for TEFAP and is continuing to make
it available at current monthly rates of 6 million pounds of
butter, 4 million pounds of cornmeal and 12 million pounds of flour.
   Thus the total TEFAP funding is $241.9 million for the remainder
of the fiscal year that began on Oct. 1, said Dianne Durant, a
spokeswoman for the department's Food and Nutrition Service.
   In addition, she said, Congress earmarked $40 million to help
feed homeless people at soup kitchens and shelters. Foods most
likely to be provided are canned pork, dry beans and canned fruit,
vegetables and juices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881015-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-88 0015EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TaxBill Bjt   10-15 0686</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tax Bill, Bjt,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House, Senate Bog Down Over How Much To Put In Tax Measure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The little tax bill that nobody loved is
hanging by a thread because House and Senate negotiators can't
agree on how big it should be.
   House negotiators are insisting on a bill that raises at least
$4.5 billion over three years, to pay for $4.5 billion of selected
tax cuts. Senators, backed by the Reagan administration, are
refusing to budge above $3 billion.
   The dispute torpedoed closed-door discussions on the bill Friday
and House aides were saying the measure probably is dead. Sen. Max
Baucus, D-Mont., who is heading the Senate delegation, was not so
pessimistic.
   ``We have not selected the pallbearers yet,'' he said, adding
that Senate aides would look over the latest House proposal over
the weekend. ``Then we'll see what the mood is next week,'' the
final week of the 100th Congress, Baucus said.
   Tax bills usually are highly popular items with members of
Congress, simply because lawmakers have found there is little that
makes voters happier than a tax cut.
   But because of a monumental budget deficit, there is no surplus
money in the treasury to finance a lot of tax cuts. So every dollar
of tax cut for Peter must be offset by a dollar tax increase on
Paul.
   That is why this year's bills are so relatively small _ about
$7.5 billion as originally passed by the House and just under $3
billion in the Senate version.
   The bills, two years in the making, have not been a top-priority
item for either the House, the Senate or the Reagan administration.
The only big push for passage has come from accountants, eager to
have some errors and ambiguities in the 1986 tax law cleared up,
and from farmers demanding relief from the tax on diesel fuel.
   Either bill would respond to those concerns. Both bills also
extend several expiring tax benefits, provide targeted relief to
lower-income homebuyers, workers attending night school, farmers
and others, and raise other taxes to pay for the benefits. The
Senate package also includes a ``bill of rights'' to help taxpayers
involved in disputes with the Internal Revenue Service.
   The exchange of offers before negotiations were broken off
indicated some form of the bill of rights will be in the final bill
_ if there is one. In addition, it would repeal the requirement
that farmers pay the diesel tax on off-road fuel and then apply for
a refund, and also prevent mutual fund owners from paying tax on
``phantom income'' from those funds.
   The negotiations are complicated by the fact that Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, is also
his party's candidate for vice president. Ever since he was
nominated in July, there have been indications he did not want to
be identified closely with a bill that opponents could point to as
new evidence of a Democratic tendency to raise taxes to finance
more spending.
   ``Senator Bentsen's position all year long has been that he is
not interested in raising a lot of taxes to be plowed back into
other tax cuts,'' said Bill Maddox, a Finance Committee spokesman.
   On the other hand, Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., head of the
House delegation, points out that his bill passed the House by a
380-25 vote _ the widest margin for a tax bill in 20 years. His
aides say it is difficult for Rostenkowski to drop provisions that
got such broad support.
   The Senate bill passed by an even more lopsided margin, 87-1.
   In backing away from their $7 billion-plus package, House
negotiators agreed to drop a money-raiser, opposed by the Reagan
administration, that would require corporations to pay more tax on
dividends from stocks they own in other companies.
   The House also agreed to modify slightly its call for repeal of
the ``completed-contract accounting'' method used by defense
contractors and many large builders. This method allows
postponement on some building profits.
   Under the proposed compromise, the benefit would be retained
only for construction of housing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
