<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AIDEmbezzler     10-15 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AID Embezzler,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Admitted Embezzler Directly To Jail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former government financial officer who
admitted embezzling $1.37 million received a stern lecture and a
five-year prison sentence from a judge who ordered him immediately
put behind bars.
   U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson ignored an
impassioned plea Friday by a defense lawyer to give William J.
Burns 10 more days with his wife and twin sons _ towheaded toddlers
who could be heard screaming outside the courtroom.
   ``I know they love Mr. Burns very much and they would very much
like him to be with them, but my responsibility is just quite
different,'' Johnson told defense attorney David R. Addis.
   Burns' wife, Kathy, a daughter from a previous marriage, and
other relatives sobbed loudly as he was led off to prison by U.S.
marshals.
   Burns pleaded guilty Aug. 11 to charges he emezzled $1.2 million
since 1982 from the Agency for International Development, where he
had worked for 21 years until his arrest last May.
   He agreed to surrender his $300,000 house and virtually all his
possessions as part of a plea agreement with Justice Department
prosecutors.
   Burns later admitted that the scheme actually began in 1980 and
included thefts that brought the total to $1.37 million,
prosecutors said.
   ``I find it significant that you persisted for over five years
in perpetrating this criminal activity against the taxpayers of the
United States,'' Johnson told Burns, explaining why she thought he
deserved a harsher sentence than recommended under the sentencing
guidelines.
   Under the guidelines, Burns would have received a sentence
ranging from 31 to 37 months. Burns must serve the full five years
of his prison sentence under a 1984 law that abolished parole for
such convictions.
   Burns was also ordered to perform 300 hours of community service
during the three years following his release from prison.
   ``You may have felt it was some faceless government, but you
were stealing from the taxpayers of the United States,'' the judge
said. ``The United States from which you stole is actually the
people who are here in the courtroom supporting you.''
   ``You violated every bit of trust that anyone had ever put in
you,'' the judge said, noting that ``in your devious manner stole
at a rate that made it difficult for it to be ascertained.''
   ``If there had not been an investigation there is no reason for
me to believe it would have stopped in May, 1988,'' the judge said.
   The scheme began to unravel late last year when AID
investigators doing a routine security check on Burns discovered he
lived in an expensive home even though his annual salary was just
over $35,000.
   Burns admitted submitting phony travel reimbursement forms to a
fictitious person in whose name he opened a bank account. He
pleaded guilty to theft, filing false claims and tax evasion.
   Prosecutor James Cole said the theft ``if not the largest, is
certainly one of the largest single thefts of public funds'' in
U.S. history. The money ``was not stolen out of a need, it was
stolen out of pure greed.''
   Cole said Burns used the money to ``buy any luxury he wanted to
lavish on himself and his family.''
   His conduct exhibited ``the attitude of `I can spend whatever I
want because I have unlimited funds in the Treasury of the United
States because of my position of trust.'''
   Among the items Burns bought were a sports car and commercial
videogames, which cost $2,500 apiece, Cole said.
   Afterwards, Addis said Burns would file an appeal of the
sentencing, which is allowed when a judge departs from the
guidelines.
</TEXT>
