<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ChildSupport     10-15 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Child Support,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Card: Child Support Enforcement Programs Need Improving</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Better enforcement is needed within programs
that compel absent parents to pay child support, Rep. Thomas
Downey, D-N.Y., said in releasing a ``report card'' that found
fault with both federal and state agencies.
   The Federal Office of Child Support Enforcement received a grade
of C on the report released Friday, while the states and
territories ran a gamut from A to F for programs to ensure that
non-custodial parents support their children.
   ``Parenting in this society has been a free ride, a joyride,''
Downey said in calling for tighter enforcement.
   ``What we're dealing with here is much more important than just
dollars,'' said Rep. Hank Brown, R-Colo., who joined Downey at the
news conference. ``Taking responsibility for your children is very
important ot these children.''
   In the United States, there are currently nearly 9 million
mothers with children whose fathers do not live with them, Downey
said. Only about 2 million of these families received their full
child support payments in 1985. Another 1 million families received
partial payments, and almost 6 million received nothing.
   ``We can and should do better,'' Downey said.
   A mandatory wage withholding provision that is included in the
welfare law signed by President Reagan on Thursday will help
resolve the problem, said Downey, who is acting chairman of the
Ways and Means subcommittee on public assistance and unemployment
compensation.
   The report card, written by the staff of the House Ways and
Means Committee, graded the Federal Office of Child Support
Enforcement based on questionnaires sent to the 54 state and
territorial child support enforcement programs. It also graded each
of the state and territorial programs based on questionnaire
responses and other data.
   Wayne Stanton, administrator of the Family Support
Administration, which oversees OCSE, said he was not displeased
with the office's showing on the report card.
   ``I think in the ultimate end, this report will tend to improve
child support around the nation, and that's what I care about,''
Stanton said.
   The OCSE, a part of the Health and Human Services Department,
was rated in nine areas, including how it establishes standards for
state child support enforcement programs; sets minimum
organizational and staffing equirements for the states; reviews and
approves state plans; conducts audits and evaluations of state
plans; and operates the federal Parent Locator Service.
   OCSE got some of its highest marks _ Bs _ for the locator
service and certifying cases in which states apply to have past-due
child support money taken out of an absent parent's income tax
refund.
   The states' grades ranged from excellent to failing, but as
Downey noted, they were marked on a curve.
   ``The state of Michigan is the valedictorian of the class,'' he
said. ``Three other states _ Delaware, New Jersey and North Dakota
_ also earned an A.''
   Seven jurisdictions flunked: Mississippi, New Mexico, Oklahoma,
Texas, West Virginia, the District of Columbia and Guam. However,
Guam failed for lack of data, the report said.
   States were graded on how they establish paternity; collect
child support; operate cost-effectively; collect interstate
payments; and reduce welfare costs.
   The average paternity establishment rate was 31 percent,
according to the report. Three states exceeded 75 percent:
Missouri, Vermont and North Dakota. States under 10 percent were
Arizona, Montana, New Hampshire, New Mexico, Oklahoma, Texas, West
Virginia and Wyoming. No data were available for three territories.
   The national average collection rate was 30 percent in cases of
families receiving Aid to Families with Dependent Children, and 39
percent in non-AFDC cases.
   The average collection cost nationwide for AFDC cases was $1.49
per dollar of administrative expense, and $2.61 in non-AFDC cases.
   States recovered about 12 percent and avoided an estimated 5
percent of AFDC costs by collecting child support.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
