<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-88 0030EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BridgesofTrust     10-15 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bridges of Trust,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US-Soviet Cultural Bridge Produces First Joint Rock Video</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: First available for Saturday AMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's not as far-reaching as arms control, but
proof that glasnost is on a roll can be seen almost daily in a
Chicago studio where U.S. and Soviet filmmakers are producing a
rock video.
   The project, the brainchild of recent philosophy graduate Robert
Kath, brings together seven students from Northwestern University
and Moscow's Victor Gerasimov Institute of Cinematography.
   The Americans spent three weeks in the Soviet Union last month,
and the Soviets are nearing the end of a similar stint here.
   Both sides are represented by full crews _ producers, directors
and cinematographers _ that have thrashed out their creative
differences for the video and an accompanying 30-minute documentary
in the finest spirit of compromise.
   ``The most surprising thing,'' Kath said, ``is how their eyes
seem to land on the same things as ours _ the jazz musicians
playing in the subway, the wealthy bankers walking down LaSalle
Street.
   ``Once we had agreed on a concept for the video, everything else
was pretty much downhill,'' he added. ``The language of film, we
discovered, was a very common thing.''
   The story line for the five-minute production is a variation on
boy-meets-girl: A young American girls dreams of dancing with the
Bolshoi Ballet, but doesn't make it, even as a young Soviet boy's
dream of coming to America is shattered.
   ``We hoped to show how we are different,'' said Soviet director
Boris Ayrapetjan, ``and yet the same, how our cultures want to be
closer, but how accomplishing that is not as easy as it should be.
   ``We could not show only sweetness and light ... but even so, we
choose to end the video with the two heroes as children again. That
way there is still hope they will achieve their goals.
   ``We must leave some hope. Otherwise,'' he continued, ``this
effort will have been senseless.''
   The music is the song ``Bridges of Trust,'' a collaborative
effort by Soviet composer Vladimir Kopisov and the American group
Collective Vision written for a peace march from Leningrad to
Moscow last year.
   Valentina, a backup singer for Prince's ``Purple Rain'' tour,
sang the lead track. Like almost everyone else associated with the
project, she donated her services.
   Each group was responsible for the costs in its country and the
bill for both the video and documentary is about $250,000.
   The video will debut at Chicago's Limelight Club next Thursday.
Depending on whether or not Kath can find a sponsor for ``Bridge,''
it could wind up being distributed to outlets ranging from MTV to
film trailers in second-run movie houses nationwide.
   The Soviets already have committed to showing the video on
national television, but Tatiana Storchak, vice president of the
Moscow film institute, said its air time will be proportional to
how successful a product it is judged to be.
   ``It is a small piece of film; we are used to working with much
longer,'' he said. ``But we have learned from our collaborators how
many images can be compacted into a short space, how we can work at
a conscious level and reach even deeper.''
</TEXT>
