<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Edward I. Koch, who was sharply criticized
by Irish-Americans after a trip to Ireland in July, got a warm
welcome from an Irish group that marched from Boston to New York on
behalf of the handicapped.
   The marchers presented Koch on Friday with a green, white and
gold rosette and ribbon, the colors of the Irish Republic.
   Frank Flannery, chief executive of the Irish Rehabilitation
Institute, said the rosette was made in one of its centers in
Ireland. He said Koch could wear it ``possibly on St. Patrick's
Day'' next year.
   ``Do you think I'll get into the parade?'' Koch quipped,
referring to next year's St. Patrick's Day parade in New York.
   ``I hope you do,'' said Flannery.
   After his trip, Koch said that British troops in Northern
Ireland were playing a ``positive role'' in preventing bloodshed
between Catholics and Protestants.
   Peter King, the Nassau County comptroller who sympathizes with
efforts to end British rule in Northern Ireland, had urged that
Koch be barred from the parade because of those comments. Koch
later apologized and said the British troops were an occupying army
that should leave within five years.
