<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-88 0034EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-WeeklyWallStreet Adv15-16   10-15 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Wall Street, Adv 15-16,0592</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Oct 15-16</NOTE>
<HEAD>Market Bulls Emphasize Contrasts With 1987</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To ward off fearsome memories on the anniversary
of Black Monday, the watchword among Wall Street's optimists is
``things are different now.''
   Many followers of the stock market have been heartened in the
past few months to see the chart of the Dow Jones industrial
average diverge from the path it followed in 1929-30.
   For many months, there was an eerie parallel in market
fluctuations during the two periods. But recently the 1988 line has
turned up where the 1930 one headed down.
   ``The main reason is that the most recent crash was not rooted
in the kind of economic problems that existed in 1928 and 1929,''
maintains Greg Smith at Prudential-Bache Securities.
   The optimists also argue that much has changed in the past year
to allay fears of a repeat of the crash of 1987.
   ``The fundamental underpinnings of the market are vastly
changed, and for the better,'' says Norman Fosback in the
investment advisory letter Market Logic.
   ``A year ago, a fundamentally overvalued market was confronted
with a sudden and rather severe tightening of monetary policy,'' he
observed. ``The result was disaster.
   ``This October, the market has already discounted a tight money
policy.''
   Fosback also stresses that stock prices, by several longstanding
measures, aren't at the dangerously high levels they reached in
1987.
   Dividend yields on the stocks that make up the major market
averages got as low as 2.5 percent at the peak of the bull market
last year.
   ``Never before in the history of the U.S. stock market had
blue-chip stocks offered such low dividend returns,'' he says.
Yields now stand in the neighborhood of 3.7 percent.
   Price-earnings ratios of those same stocks, which surpassed 20
to 1 last summer, now hover around 12 to 1. Today's yields and PEs
``are at approximately normal levels,'' by Fosback's reckoning.
   ``Perhaps more importantly, if corporate earnings continue to
grow at their current pace and the market rises to last year's
high, PE ratios would still be below their historical norm.''
   In the past week, the market reached its highest levels since
the crash, but then settled back. Dow Jones's average of 30 blue
chips closed Friday at 2,133.18, down 17.07 from the week before.
   The New York Stock Exchange composite index dropped 1.35 to
155.46; the NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
lost 1.08 to 384.59, and the American Stock Exchange market value
index was down 1.27 at 302.55.
   Volume on the Big Board averaged 147.05 million shares a day,
against 166.65 million the week before.
   Fosback says he is by no means arguing that stocks are at
deep-discount bargain levels right now.
   But he adds, ``the key consideration is that they are far from
overvalued. Strong bull markets began in 1966 and 1970 from PE
ratio levels that were actually higher than that which prevails
today.
   ``Obviously, October 19 COULD recur,'' he acknowledges. ``It
happened once; it can certainly happen again.
   ``The more meaningful question is, is it likely to happen any
time soon? To this, the answer must be a resounding no.
   ``Investors have no need to fear a near-term replay of Oct. 19,
1987. Indeed, current readings on the classic fundamental
indicators are fully consistent with a bull market scenario.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Oct. 15-16</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881015-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-88 0000EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-WeeklyCommodities Adv15-16   10-14 0785</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Commodities, Adv 15-16,0804</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 15</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Oct. 15-16</NOTE>
<HEAD>First New Stock Index Future Since Crash Seen As Opportunity For
Arbitrage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To be followed later in cycle with an ADD containing weekly
commodity price trends</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A soon-to-be released product called the CBOE 250 is so eagerly
anticipated that its introduction has been delayed to make sure
everyone who wants it can get it.
   No, it's not a car or a computer _ it's a new stock-index
futures contract, the first to be approved by federal regulators
since last year's stock-market collapse.
   It's also the first futures contract that will trade on the
floor of the Chicago Board Options Exchange and the first major
offering of a joint venture between the CBOE and the Chicago Board
of Trade, the world's largest futures market.
   The Board of Trade and the CBOE, the world's largest options
exchange, expected about 200 of their members to sign up to trade
CBOE 250 futures. Instead, more than 500 people have expressed
their intention to participate in the market, forcing the exchanges
to postpone the contract's launch date from Nov. 1 to Nov. 11.
   ``This is the first time we've ever put off the launch of a
contract because of something like this,'' said CBOT spokesman Ray
Carmichael. ``It could even be that we'll have to put it off beyond
the 11th, but we still hope to launch it on that date.''
   The contract is based on the CBOE 250 stock index, which
measures the composite performance of the 250 largest stocks traded
on the New York Stock Exchange.
   The futures contract will allow investors to speculate on the
index's performance by committing themselves to buy or sell a
basket of the underlying stocks for a specified price on a
specified future date.
   The most important feature of the new contract, according to
CBOE operations planner William Barclay, is that it will allow
players in the CBOE's popular stock index options markets to hedge
against losses there, thus reducing their risk and the overall risk
of the markets.
   A stock-index option gives the holder an option _ but not an
obligation _ to buy or sell a basket of stocks at a specified price
on a specified future date.
   An investor who has bet, via the options market, on a rise in
the stock market could hedge against a loss on that investment by
selling a CBOE 250 futures contract or vice versa.
   Because futures trading concepts may be unfamiliar to some CBOE
members, those who want to trade CBOE 250 index futures are
required to take a futures-trading course and pass a test
authorized by the Commodity Futures Trading Commission, the federal
agency that regulates U.S. futures and options markets.
   Meanwhile, members of the Board of Trade seeking to participate
in the new market are not allowed on the CBOE floor without first
attending orientation classes to learn about floor rules peculiar
to the exchange.
   All this processing and training is causing the hold-up in
launching the new contract, officials said.
   Although four other stock-index futures are traded on U.S.
exchanges _ with the most successful by far being the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange's Standard & Poor's 500 contract _ the CBOE 250
will be the first launched since the stock market's collapse last
Oct. 19.
   The crash focused public attention on stock-index futures. The
Securities and Exchange Commission said certain types of
sophisticated trading activities involving index futures may have
accelerated the collapse.
   A handful of brokerage houses curtailed their involvement in
those trading activities _ called program trading and index
arbitrage _ in the wake of the publicity that developed.
   In index arbitrage, traders sell in one market while
simultaneously buying in another in an attempt to profit from the
constantly changing prices in both markets. One type of program
trading involves the use of computers for arbitrage trades of huge
blocks of stocks and stock-index futures contracts.
   Despite the withdrawal of a few firms from such activities,
analysts say index arbitrage and program trading now play an even
larger role in the financial markets because many smaller, less
sophisticated investors who fled the markets after the crash have
not returned.
   The CBOE 250 index futures will likely become just one more
avenue for arbitrage, said Jack Barbanel, director of futures
trading with Gruntal & Co. in New York.
   ``The only benefit I can see of that contract is that it
provides some interesting arbitrage opportunities between CBOE
options and the futures contract,'' he said. ``It will enable you
to use a combination of hedging and arbitrage strategies and that
is really its greatest marketing advantage.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
