<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Bonds, Adv 15-16,0670</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 15</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Oct. 15-16</NOTE>
<HEAD>Future Uncertain for Texas Air Companies' High-Yield Bonds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sale of Eastern Airlines' profitable shuttle
service to casino-hotel tycoon Donald Trump for $365 million in
cash titillated the airline industry and conjured up images of slot
machines aboard glitzy jets plying the Northeast corridor.
   Trump's deal with Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo,
announced this past Wednesday after a week of speculation, had more
practical effects, too.
   Among its more notable results, the sale of the three-city
shuttle gave a shot in the arm to the flagging ``junk'' bonds
issued by Eastern, its parent Texas Air and its sister carrier
Continental Airlines.
   But the longer-term outlook for the high-risk, high-yield issues
is less clear, analysts say. They warn that Lorenzo's desire for
liquid funds may have crippled Eastern's earnings potential.
   When word of talks on the shuttle between Trump and Lorenzo was
leaked in advance to the press, prices of the securities started
climbing, pushing their yields lower.
   ``The bond market knew this was coming,'' said Ray Neidl, a
senior bond analyst for McCarthy, Crisanti & Maffei Inc.
   The yield on Texas Air's 14.25 percent issue due in 1993, for
example, had dropped to 15.87 percent this past Friday from nearly
17 percent before the leaks on the shuttle negotiations.
   The highly leveraged Texas Air (excluding its subsidiaries) has
a total of around $525 million in bond issues outstanding. Eastern
has nearly $700 million, while Continental has a hefty $1.8
billion. The latter includes securities issued by the now-defunct
New York Air and People Express, absorbed by Continental in
February 1987.
   After Trump and Lorenzo triumphantly proclaimed the shuttle sale
to reporters at Trump's tony Plaza Hotel in Manhattan, Standard &
Poor's Corp. announced that it was keeping a close eye on
Miami-based Eastern in the wake of the acquisition.
   Calling the $365 million anted up by Trump ``a generous price,''
the credit-rating agency said the interest on that sum could
recover more than half the cash flow that would be lost by selling
the shuttle.
   Standard & Poor's had previously given Eastern's equipment trust
certificates, senior industrial revenue bonds and convertible
debentures ratings of single B, triple CCC and double CC,
respectively. The agency's announcement hinted that those ratings
might be raised in light of the shuttle sale.
   ``It's because they get a cash infusion at Eastern,'' noted
Michael Dahood, a corporate bond expert at Smith Barney, Upham & Co.
   That's the reason for the bullishness affecting the Texas Air
and Eastern issues. The sale, on which Eastern is expected to clear
about $240 million, gives Lorenzo a formidable war chest to
withstand a strike by Eastern's militant unions.
   The positive impact on Continental bonds is more subtle,
however. Lorenzo said he has been approached by financier Carl
Icahn, the wily chairman of Trans World Airlines Inc., about
possibly buying the rest of Eastern.
   The shuttle sale signaled to the bond market that Lorenzo could
be open to the idea of unloading the rest of Eastern to Icahn or
another suitor _ a move that would focus Texas Air's energy and
cash on Houston-based Continental.
   Despite the bullishness, however, analysts warn that Texas Air
may have sacrificed Eastern's potential future earnings on the
altar of quick cash.
   ``They sold their best-performing asset,'' said Richard Bilotti,
a vice president of the high-yield bond department at Prudential
Bache Securities Inc. ``That's not a good thing for the long term.''
   Analysts have estimated that the shuttle has a potential cash
flow of around $70 million a year.
   A negative report of Eastern earnings or a strike at the carrier
could quickly knock down the prices of the bonds, Bilotti warned.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Oct. 15-16</NOTE>
