<HEAD>UNDATED: .... marketing advantage.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here are some commodity price trends during the past week:
   Grain and soybean futures were mixed on the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   Wheat for December delivery settled Friday at $4.28} a bushel,
down from from $4.34{ a week earlier; December corn slipped to
$2.93} a bushel from $2.94{; December oats rallied to $2.52{ a
bushel from $2.44{; and November soybeans rose to $8.04 a bushel
from $7.90.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   October live cattle rose to 72.87 cents a pound from 72.32
cents; October feeder cattle fell to 82 cents a pound from 82.30
cents; October hogs dipped to 40.42 cents a pound from 40.45 cents;
and February frozen pork bellies rose to 49 cents a pound from
47.52 cents.
   Precious metals future advanced on the Commodity Exchange in New
York.
   December gold rose to $412.50 a troy ounce from $407.30;
December silver rose to $6.435 a troy ounce from $6.405.
   Energy futures moved sharply higher on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
   November West Texas Intermediate crude oil surged to $14.92 a
barrel from $12.94; October heating oil rallied to 43.21 cents a
gallon from 37.46 cents; and October unleaded gasoline rose to
45.42 cents a gallon from 40.13 cents.
</TEXT>
